  version: {fileID: 11400000, guid: 51ee3e37f5ded7941ab6216610f6fc67, type: 2}
  description: 
  chapters:
  - verses:
    - title: The Israelites in Egypt
      content: '  These are the names of the sons of Israel (that is, Jacob) who
        moved to Egypt with their father, each with his family: '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Reuben, Simeon, Levi, Judah, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Issachar, Zebulun, Benjamin, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Dan, Naphtali, Gad, and Asher. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'In all, Jacob had seventy[[COMMENT(0)]] descendants in Egypt, including
        Joseph, who was already there.  '
      comments:
      - number: '1:5 '
        content: Dead Sea Scrolls and Greek version read <b>seventy-five; </b>see
          notes on Gen 46:27.
    - title: 
      content: 'In time, Joseph and all of his brothers died, ending that entire
        generation. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But their descendants, the Israelites, had many children and grandchildren.
        In fact, they multiplied so greatly that they became extremely powerful and
        filled the land.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Eventually, a new king came to power in Egypt who knew nothing about
        Joseph or what he had done. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He said to his people, \u201CLook, the people of Israel now outnumber
        us and are stronger than we are. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "We must make a plan to keep them from growing even more. If we don\u2019t,
        and if war breaks out, they will join our enemies and fight against us. Then
        they will escape from the country.[[COMMENT(0)]]\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '1:10 '
        content: Or <b>will take the country.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'So the Egyptians made the Israelites their slaves. They appointed
        brutal slave drivers over them, hoping to wear them down with crushing labor.
        They forced them to build the cities of Pithom and Rameses as supply centers
        for the king. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But the more the Egyptians oppressed them, the more the Israelites
        multiplied and spread, and the more alarmed the Egyptians became. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So the Egyptians worked the people of Israel without mercy. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They made their lives bitter, forcing them to mix mortar and make
        bricks and do all the work in the fields. They were ruthless in all their
        demands.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then Pharaoh, the king of Egypt, gave this order to the Hebrew midwives,
        Shiphrah and Puah: '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWhen you help the Hebrew women as they give birth, watch as
        they deliver.[[COMMENT(0)]] If the baby is a boy, kill him; if it is a girl,
        let her live.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: '1:16 '
        content: Hebrew <b>look upon the two stones; </b>perhaps the reference is
          to a birthstool.
    - title: 
      content: "But because the midwives feared God, they refused to obey the king\u2019s
        orders. They allowed the boys to live, too.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So the king of Egypt called for the midwives. \u201CWhy have you
        done this?\u201D he demanded. \u201CWhy have you allowed the boys to live?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThe Hebrew women are not like the Egyptian women,\u201D the
        midwives replied. \u201CThey are more vigorous and have their babies so quickly
        that we cannot get there in time.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So God was good to the midwives, and the Israelites continued to
        multiply, growing more and more powerful. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And because the midwives feared God, he gave them families of their
        own.  '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: The Birth of Moses
      content: '  About this time, a man and woman from the tribe of Levi got married. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The woman became pregnant and gave birth to a son. She saw that he
        was a special baby and kept him hidden for three months. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But when she could no longer hide him, she got a basket made of papyrus
        reeds and waterproofed it with tar and pitch. She put the baby in the basket
        and laid it among the reeds along the bank of the Nile River. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The baby\u2019s sister then stood at a distance, watching to see
        what would happen to him.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Soon Pharaoh\u2019s daughter came down to bathe in the river, and
        her attendants walked along the riverbank. When the princess saw the basket
        among the reeds, she sent her maid to get it for her. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When the princess opened it, she saw the baby. The little boy was
        crying, and she felt sorry for him. \u201CThis must be one of the Hebrew
        children,\u201D she said.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then the baby\u2019s sister approached the princess. \u201CShould
        I go and find one of the Hebrew women to nurse the baby for you?\u201D she
        asked.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CYes, do!\u201D the princess replied. So the girl went and called
        the baby\u2019s mother.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CTake this baby and nurse him for me,\u201D the princess told
        the baby\u2019s mother. \u201CI will pay you for your help.\u201D So the
        woman took her baby home and nursed him.  "
      comments: []
    - title: Moses Escapes to Midian
      content: "Later, when the boy was older, his mother brought him back to Pharaoh\u2019s
        daughter, who adopted him as her own son. The princess named him Moses,[[COMMENT(0)]]
        for she explained, \u201CI lifted him out of the water.\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '2:10 '
        content: "<b>Moses </b>sounds like a Hebrew term that means \u201Cto lift
          out.\u201D"
    - title: 
      content: 'Many years later, when Moses had grown up, he went out to visit his
        own people, the Hebrews, and he saw how hard they were forced to work. During
        his visit, he saw an Egyptian beating one of his fellow Hebrews. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'After looking in all directions to make sure no one was watching,
        Moses killed the Egyptian and hid the body in the sand.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The next day, when Moses went out to visit his people again, he saw
        two Hebrew men fighting. \u201CWhy are you beating up your friend?\u201D
        Moses said to the one who had started the fight.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The man replied, \u201CWho appointed you to be our prince and judge?
        Are you going to kill me as you killed that Egyptian yesterday?\u201DThen
        Moses was afraid, thinking, \u201CEveryone knows what I did.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And sure enough, Pharaoh heard what had happened, and he tried to
        kill Moses. But Moses fled from Pharaoh and went to live in the land of Midian.When
        Moses arrived in Midian, he sat down beside a well. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Now the priest of Midian had seven daughters who came as usual to
        draw water and fill the water troughs for their father\u2019s flocks. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But some other shepherds came and chased them away. So Moses jumped
        up and rescued the girls from the shepherds. Then he drew water for their
        flocks.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When the girls returned to Reuel, their father, he asked, \u201CWhy
        are you back so soon today?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CAn Egyptian rescued us from the shepherds,\u201D they answered.
        \u201CAnd then he drew water for us and watered our flocks.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThen where is he?\u201D their father asked. \u201CWhy did you
        leave him there? Invite him to come and eat with us.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Moses accepted the invitation, and he settled there with him. In
        time, Reuel gave Moses his daughter Zipporah to be his wife. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Later she gave birth to a son, and Moses named him Gershom,[[COMMENT(0)]]
        for he explained, \u201CI have been a foreigner in a foreign land.\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '2:22 '
        content: "<b>Gershom </b>sounds like a Hebrew term that means \u201Ca foreigner
          there.\u201D"
    - title: 
      content: 'Years passed, and the king of Egypt died. But the Israelites continued
        to groan under their burden of slavery. They cried out for help, and their
        cry rose up to God. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'God heard their groaning, and he remembered his covenant promise
        to Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob. '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Moses and the Burning Bush
      content: '  One day Moses was tending the flock of his father-in-law, Jethro,[[COMMENT(0)]]
        the priest of Midian. He led the flock far into the wilderness and came to
        Sinai,[[COMMENT(1)]] the mountain of God. '
      comments:
      - number: '3:1a '
        content: "Moses\u2019 father-in-law went by two names, Jethro and Reuel."
      - number: '3:1b '
        content: Hebrew <b>Horeb, </b>another name for Sinai.
    - title: 
      content: "There the angel of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> appeared to him
        in a blazing fire from the middle of a bush. Moses stared in amazement. Though
        the bush was engulfed in flames, it didn\u2019t burn up. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThis is amazing,\u201D Moses said to himself. \u201CWhy isn\u2019t
        that bush burning up? I must go see it.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> saw Moses coming to take a closer
        look, God called to him from the middle of the bush, \u201CMoses! Moses!\u201D\u201CHere
        I am!\u201D Moses replied.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CDo not come any closer,\u201D the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        warned. \u201CTake off your sandals, for you are standing on holy ground. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "I am the God of your father[[COMMENT(0)]]\u2014the God of Abraham,
        the God of Isaac, and the God of Jacob.\u201D When Moses heard this, he covered
        his face because he was afraid to look at God.  "
      comments:
      - number: '3:6 '
        content: Greek version reads <b>your fathers.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> told him, \u201CI have certainly
        seen the oppression of my people in Egypt. I have heard their cries of distress
        because of their harsh slave drivers. Yes, I am aware of their suffering. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So I have come down to rescue them from the power of the Egyptians
        and lead them out of Egypt into their own fertile and spacious land. It is
        a land flowing with milk and honey\u2014the land where the Canaanites, Hittites,
        Amorites, Perizzites, Hivites, and Jebusites now live. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Look! The cry of the people of Israel has reached me, and I have
        seen how harshly the Egyptians abuse them. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Now go, for I am sending you to Pharaoh. You must lead my people
        Israel out of Egypt.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But Moses protested to God, \u201CWho am I to appear before Pharaoh?
        Who am I to lead the people of Israel out of Egypt?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "God answered, \u201CI will be with you. And this is your sign that
        I am the one who has sent you: When you have brought the people out of Egypt,
        you will worship God at this very mountain.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But Moses protested, \u201CIf I go to the people of Israel and tell
        them, \u2018The God of your ancestors has sent me to you,\u2019 they will
        ask me, \u2018What is his name?\u2019 Then what should I tell them?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "God replied to Moses, \u201C<smallcaps>I Am Who I Am</smallcaps>.[[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>
        Say this to the people of Israel: </smallcaps><smallcaps>I Am</smallcaps>
        has sent me to you.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: '3:14 '
        content: Or <b><span class="ChapterContent_nd__ECPAf">I Will Be What I Will
          Be.</span></b>
    - title: 
      content: "God also said to Moses, \u201CSay this to the people of Israel: Yahweh,[[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>
        the God of your ancestors\u2014the God of Abraham, the God of Isaac, and
        the God of Jacob\u2014has sent me to you.</smallcaps>This is my eternal name,my
        name to remember for all generations.  "
      comments:
      - number: '3:15 '
        content: "<b>Yahweh </b>(also in 3:16) is a transliteration of the proper
          name <b>YHWH </b>that is sometimes rendered \u201CJehovah\u201D; in this
          translation it is usually rendered \u201Cthe <span class=\"ChapterContent_nd__ECPAf\">Lord</span>\u201D
          (note the use of small capitals)."
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CNow go and call together all the elders of Israel. Tell them,
        \u2018Yahweh, the God of your ancestors\u2014the God of Abraham, Isaac, and
        Jacob\u2014has appeared to me. He told me, \u201CI have been watching closely,
        and I see how the Egyptians are treating you. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "I have promised to rescue you from your oppression in Egypt. I will
        lead you to a land flowing with milk and honey\u2014the land where the Canaanites,
        Hittites, Amorites, Perizzites, Hivites, and Jebusites now live.\u201D\u2019  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThe elders of Israel will accept your message. Then you and
        the elders must go to the king of Egypt and tell him, \u2018The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        the God of the Hebrews, has met with us. So please let us take a three-day
        journey into the wilderness to offer sacrifices to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        our God.\u2019  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CBut I know that the king of Egypt will not let you go unless
        a mighty hand forces him.[[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '3:19 '
        content: As in Greek and Latin versions; Hebrew reads <b>will not let you
          go, not by a mighty hand.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'So I will raise my hand and strike the Egyptians, performing all
        kinds of miracles among them. Then at last he will let you go. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And I will cause the Egyptians to look favorably on you. They will
        give you gifts when you go so you will not leave empty-handed. '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: "Signs of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s Power"
      content: "  But Moses protested again, \u201CWhat if they won\u2019t believe
        me or listen to me? What if they say, \u2018The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        never appeared to you\u2019?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> asked him, \u201CWhat is that
        in your hand?\u201D\u201CA shepherd\u2019s staff,\u201D Moses replied.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThrow it down on the ground,\u201D the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        told him. So Moses threw down the staff, and it turned into a snake! Moses
        jumped back.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> told him, \u201CReach out and
        grab its tail.\u201D So Moses reached out and grabbed it, and it turned back
        into a shepherd\u2019s staff in his hand.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CPerform this sign,\u201D the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> told
        him. \u201CThen they will believe that the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the
        God of their ancestors\u2014the God of Abraham, the God of Isaac, and the
        God of Jacob\u2014really has appeared to you.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to Moses, \u201CNow put
        your hand inside your cloak.\u201D So Moses put his hand inside his cloak,
        and when he took it out again, his hand was white as snow with a severe skin
        disease.[[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '4:6 '
        content: Or <b>with leprosy. </b>The Hebrew word used here can describe various
          skin diseases.
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CNow put your hand back into your cloak,\u201D the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        said. So Moses put his hand back in, and when he took it out again, it was
        as healthy as the rest of his body.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to Moses, \u201CIf they do not
        believe you and are not convinced by the first miraculous sign, they will
        be convinced by the second sign. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And if they don\u2019t believe you or listen to you even after these
        two signs, then take some water from the Nile River and pour it out on the
        dry ground. When you do, the water from the Nile will turn to blood on the
        ground.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But Moses pleaded with the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, \u201CO Lord,
        I\u2019m not very good with words. I never have been, and I\u2019m not now,
        even though you have spoken to me. I get tongue-tied, and my words get tangled.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> asked Moses, \u201CWho makes
        a person\u2019s mouth? Who decides whether people speak or do not speak,
        hear or do not hear, see or do not see? Is it not I, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>? "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Now go! I will be with you as you speak, and I will instruct you
        in what to say.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But Moses again pleaded, \u201CLord, please! Send anyone else.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> became angry with Moses. \u201CAll
        right,\u201D he said. \u201CWhat about your brother, Aaron the Levite? I
        know he speaks well. And look! He is on his way to meet you now. He will
        be delighted to see you. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Talk to him, and put the words in his mouth. I will be with both
        of you as you speak, and I will instruct you both in what to do. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Aaron will be your spokesman to the people. He will be your mouthpiece,
        and you will stand in the place of God for him, telling him what to say. '
      comments: []
    - title: Moses Returns to Egypt
      content: "And take your shepherd\u2019s staff with you, and use it to perform
        the miraculous signs I have shown you.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So Moses went back home to Jethro, his father-in-law. \u201CPlease
        let me return to my relatives in Egypt,\u201D Moses said. \u201CI don\u2019t
        even know if they are still alive.\u201D\u201CGo in peace,\u201D Jethro replied.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Before Moses left Midian, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to
        him, \u201CReturn to Egypt, for all those who wanted to kill you have died.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So Moses took his wife and sons, put them on a donkey, and headed
        back to the land of Egypt. In his hand he carried the staff of God.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> told Moses, \u201CWhen you arrive
        back in Egypt, go to Pharaoh and perform all the miracles I have empowered
        you to do. But I will harden his heart so he will refuse to let the people
        go. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then you will tell him, \u2018This is what the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        says: Israel is my firstborn son. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "I commanded you, \u201CLet my son go, so he can worship me.\u201D
        But since you have refused, I will now kill your firstborn son!\u2019\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'On the way to Egypt, at a place where Moses and his family had stopped
        for the night, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> confronted him and was about
        to kill him. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But Moses\u2019 wife, Zipporah, took a flint knife and circumcised
        her son. She touched his feet[[COMMENT(0)]] with the foreskin and said, \u201CNow
        you are a bridegroom of blood to me.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: '4:25 '
        content: "The Hebrew word for \u201Cfeet\u201D may refer here to the male
          sex organ."
    - title: 
      content: "(When she said \u201Ca bridegroom of blood,\u201D she was referring
        to the circumcision.) After that, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> left him
        alone.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Now the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had said to Aaron, \u201CGo out
        into the wilderness to meet Moses.\u201D So Aaron went and met Moses at the
        mountain of God, and he embraced him. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Moses then told Aaron everything the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        had commanded him to say. And he told him about the miraculous signs the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had commanded him to perform.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then Moses and Aaron returned to Egypt and called all the elders
        of Israel together. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Aaron told them everything the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had told
        Moses, and Moses performed the miraculous signs as they watched. '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Moses and Aaron Speak to Pharaoh
      content: "  After this presentation to Israel\u2019s leaders, Moses and Aaron
        went and spoke to Pharaoh. They told him, \u201CThis is what the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        the God of Israel, says: Let my people go so they may hold a festival in
        my honor in the wilderness.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CIs that so?\u201D retorted Pharaoh. \u201CAnd who is the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>?
        Why should I listen to him and let Israel go? I don\u2019t know the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        and I will not let Israel go.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But Aaron and Moses persisted. \u201CThe God of the Hebrews has met
        with us,\u201D they declared. \u201CSo let us take a three-day journey into
        the wilderness so we can offer sacrifices to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        our God. If we don\u2019t, he will kill us with a plague or with the sword.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Pharaoh replied, \u201CMoses and Aaron, why are you distracting the
        people from their tasks? Get back to work! "
      comments: []
    - title: Making Bricks without Straw
      content: "Look, there are many of your people in the land, and you are stopping
        them from their work.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'That same day Pharaoh sent this order to the Egyptian slave drivers
        and the Israelite foremen: '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CDo not supply any more straw for making bricks. Make the people
        get it themselves! "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But still require them to make the same number of bricks as before.
        Don\u2019t reduce the quota. They are lazy. That\u2019s why they are crying
        out, \u2018Let us go and offer sacrifices to our God.\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Load them down with more work. Make them sweat! That will teach them
        to listen to lies!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So the slave drivers and foremen went out and told the people: \u201CThis
        is what Pharaoh says: I will not provide any more straw for you. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Go and get it yourselves. Find it wherever you can. But you must
        produce just as many bricks as before!\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So the people scattered throughout the land of Egypt in search of
        stubble to use as straw.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Meanwhile, the Egyptian slave drivers continued to push hard. \u201CMeet
        your daily quota of bricks, just as you did when we provided you with straw!\u201D
        they demanded. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then they whipped the Israelite foremen they had put in charge of
        the work crews. \u201CWhy haven\u2019t you met your quotas either yesterday
        or today?\u201D they demanded.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So the Israelite foremen went to Pharaoh and pleaded with him. \u201CPlease
        don\u2019t treat your servants like this,\u201D they begged. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWe are given no straw, but the slave drivers still demand,
        \u2018Make bricks!\u2019 We are being beaten, but it isn\u2019t our fault!
        Your own people are to blame!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But Pharaoh shouted, \u201CYou\u2019re just lazy! Lazy! That\u2019s
        why you\u2019re saying, \u2018Let us go and offer sacrifices to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Now get back to work! No straw will be given to you, but you must
        still produce the full quota of bricks.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The Israelite foremen could see that they were in serious trouble
        when they were told, \u201CYou must not reduce the number of bricks you make
        each day.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "As they left Pharaoh\u2019s court, they confronted Moses and Aaron,
        who were waiting outside for them. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The foremen said to them, \u201CMay the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        judge and punish you for making us stink before Pharaoh and his officials.
        You have put a sword into their hands, an excuse to kill us!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Moses went back to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> and protested,
        \u201CWhy have you brought all this trouble on your own people, Lord? Why
        did you send me? "
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Promises of Deliverance
      content: "  Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> told Moses, \u201CNow you
        will see what I will do to Pharaoh. When he feels the force of my strong
        hand, he will let the people go. In fact, he will force them to leave his
        land!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And God said to Moses, \u201CI am Yahweh\u2014\u2018the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.\u2019[[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps> 
        </smallcaps>"
      comments:
      - number: '6:2 '
        content: "<b>Yahweh </b>is a transliteration of the proper name <b>YHWH </b>that
          is sometimes rendered \u201CJehovah\u201D; in this translation it is usually
          rendered \u201Cthe <span class=\"ChapterContent_nd__ECPAf\">Lord</span>\u201D
          (note the use of small capitals)."
    - title: 
      content: "I appeared to Abraham, to Isaac, and to Jacob as El-Shaddai\u2014\u2018God
        Almighty\u2019[[COMMENT(0)]]\u2014but I did not reveal my name, Yahweh, to
        them. "
      comments:
      - number: '6:3 '
        content: "<b>El-Shaddai, </b>which means \u201CGod Almighty,\u201D is the
          name for God used in Gen 17:1; 28:3; 35:11; 43:14; 48:3."
    - title: 
      content: 'And I reaffirmed my covenant with them. Under its terms, I promised
        to give them the land of Canaan, where they were living as foreigners. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'You can be sure that I have heard the groans of the people of Israel,
        who are now slaves to the Egyptians. And I am well aware of my covenant with
        them.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CTherefore, say to the people of Israel: \u2018I am the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.
        I will free you from your oppression and will rescue you from your slavery
        in Egypt. I will redeem you with a powerful arm and great acts of judgment. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I will claim you as my own people, and I will be your God. Then you
        will know that I am the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> your God who has freed
        you from your oppression in Egypt. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "I will bring you into the land I swore to give to Abraham, Isaac,
        and Jacob. I will give it to you as your very own possession. I am the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>!\u2019\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So Moses told the people of Israel what the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        had said, but they refused to listen anymore. They had become too discouraged
        by the brutality of their slavery.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to Moses, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CGo back to Pharaoh, the king of Egypt, and tell him to let
        the people of Israel leave his country.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CBut <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>!\u201D Moses objected. \u201CMy
        own people won\u2019t listen to me anymore. How can I expect Pharaoh to listen?
        I\u2019m such a clumsy speaker![[COMMENT(0)]]\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '6:12 '
        content: Hebrew <b>I have uncircumcised lips; </b>also in 6:30.
    - title: The Ancestors of Moses and Aaron
      content: 'But the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> spoke to Moses and Aaron and
        gave them orders for the Israelites and for Pharaoh, the king of Egypt. The
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> commanded Moses and Aaron to lead the people
        of Israel out of Egypt.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "These are the ancestors of some of the clans of Israel:The sons of
        Reuben, Israel\u2019s oldest son, were Hanoch, Pallu, Hezron, and Carmi.
        Their descendants became the clans of Reuben.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The sons of Simeon were Jemuel, Jamin, Ohad, Jakin, Zohar, and Shaul.
        (Shaul\u2019s mother was a Canaanite woman.) Their descendants became the
        clans of Simeon.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'These are the descendants of Levi, as listed in their family records:
        The sons of Levi were Gershon, Kohath, and Merari. (Levi lived to be 137
        years old.)  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The descendants of Gershon included Libni and Shimei, each of whom
        became the ancestor of a clan.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The descendants of Kohath included Amram, Izhar, Hebron, and Uzziel.
        (Kohath lived to be 133 years old.)  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The descendants of Merari included Mahli and Mushi.These are the
        clans of the Levites, as listed in their family records.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Amram married his father\u2019s sister Jochebed, and she gave birth
        to his sons, Aaron and Moses. (Amram lived to be 137 years old.)  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The sons of Izhar were Korah, Nepheg, and Zicri.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The sons of Uzziel were Mishael, Elzaphan, and Sithri.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Aaron married Elisheba, the daughter of Amminadab and sister of Nahshon,
        and she gave birth to his sons, Nadab, Abihu, Eleazar, and Ithamar.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The sons of Korah were Assir, Elkanah, and Abiasaph. Their descendants
        became the clans of Korah.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Eleazar son of Aaron married one of the daughters of Putiel, and
        she gave birth to his son, Phinehas.These are the ancestors of the Levite
        families, listed according to their clans.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The Aaron and Moses named in this list are the same ones to whom
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said, \u201CLead the people of Israel out
        of the land of Egypt like an army.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'It was Moses and Aaron who spoke to Pharaoh, the king of Egypt, about
        leading the people of Israel out of Egypt.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> spoke to Moses in the land of
        Egypt, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "he said to him, \u201CI am the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>! Tell
        Pharaoh, the king of Egypt, everything I am telling you.\u201D "
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: "Aaron\u2019s Staff Becomes a Serpent"
      content: "  Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to Moses, \u201CPay close
        attention to this. I will make you seem like God to Pharaoh, and your brother,
        Aaron, will be your prophet. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Tell Aaron everything I command you, and Aaron must command Pharaoh
        to let the people of Israel leave his country. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But I will make Pharaoh\u2019s heart stubborn so I can multiply my
        miraculous signs and wonders in the land of Egypt. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Even then Pharaoh will refuse to listen to you. So I will bring down
        my fist on Egypt. Then I will rescue my forces\u2014my people, the Israelites\u2014from
        the land of Egypt with great acts of judgment. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When I raise my powerful hand and bring out the Israelites, the Egyptians
        will know that I am the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So Moses and Aaron did just as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had
        commanded them. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Moses was eighty years old, and Aaron was eighty-three when they
        made their demands to Pharaoh.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to Moses and Aaron, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CPharaoh will demand, \u2018Show me a miracle.\u2019 When he
        does this, say to Aaron, \u2018Take your staff and throw it down in front
        of Pharaoh, and it will become a serpent.[[COMMENT(0)]]\u2019\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '7:9 '
        content: "Hebrew <b>tannin, </b>which elsewhere refers to a sea monster.
          Greek version translates it \u201Cdragon.\u201D"
    - title: 
      content: 'So Moses and Aaron went to Pharaoh and did what the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        had commanded them. Aaron threw down his staff before Pharaoh and his officials,
        and it became a serpent! '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then Pharaoh called in his own wise men and sorcerers, and these
        Egyptian magicians did the same thing with their magic. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "They threw down their staffs, which also became serpents! But then
        Aaron\u2019s staff swallowed up their staffs. "
      comments: []
    - title: A Plague of Blood
      content: "Pharaoh\u2019s heart, however, remained hard. He still refused to
        listen, just as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had predicted.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to Moses, \u201CPharaoh\u2019s
        heart is stubborn,[[COMMENT(0)]] and he still refuses to let the people go. "
      comments:
      - number: '7:14 '
        content: Hebrew <b>heavy.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'So go to Pharaoh in the morning as he goes down to the river. Stand
        on the bank of the Nile and meet him there. Be sure to take along the staff
        that turned into a snake. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then announce to him, \u2018The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the
        God of the Hebrews, has sent me to tell you, \u201CLet my people go, so they
        can worship me in the wilderness.\u201D Until now, you have refused to listen
        to him. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So this is what the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> says: \u201CI will
        show you that I am the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.\u201D Look! I will strike
        the water of the Nile with this staff in my hand, and the river will turn
        to blood. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The fish in it will die, and the river will stink. The Egyptians
        will not be able to drink any water from the Nile.\u2019\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to Moses: \u201CTell Aaron,
        \u2018Take your staff and raise your hand over the waters of Egypt\u2014all
        its rivers, canals, ponds, and all the reservoirs. Turn all the water to
        blood. Everywhere in Egypt the water will turn to blood, even the water stored
        in wooden bowls and stone pots.\u2019\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So Moses and Aaron did just as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> commanded
        them. As Pharaoh and all of his officials watched, Aaron raised his staff
        and struck the water of the Nile. Suddenly, the whole river turned to blood! '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The fish in the river died, and the water became so foul that the
        Egyptians couldn\u2019t drink it. There was blood everywhere throughout the
        land of Egypt. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But again the magicians of Egypt used their magic, and they, too,
        turned water into blood. So Pharaoh\u2019s heart remained hard. He refused
        to listen to Moses and Aaron, just as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had
        predicted. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Pharaoh returned to his palace and put the whole thing out of his
        mind. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then all the Egyptians dug along the riverbank to find drinking water,
        for they couldn\u2019t drink the water from the Nile.  "
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: A Plague of Frogs
      content: "    [[COMMENT(0)]]Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to Moses,
        \u201CGo back to Pharaoh and announce to him, \u2018This is what the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        says: Let my people go, so they can worship me. "
      comments:
      - number: '8:1 '
        content: '  Verses 8:1-4 are numbered 7:26-29 in Hebrew text.    '
    - title: 
      content: 'If you refuse to let them go, I will send a plague of frogs across
        your entire land. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The Nile River will swarm with frogs. They will come up out of the
        river and into your palace, even into your bedroom and onto your bed! They
        will enter the houses of your officials and your people. They will even jump
        into your ovens and your kneading bowls. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Frogs will jump on you, your people, and all your officials.\u2019\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "  [[COMMENT(0)]]Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to Moses,
        \u201CTell Aaron, \u2018Raise the staff in your hand over all the rivers,
        canals, and ponds of Egypt, and bring up frogs over all the land.\u2019\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: '8:5 '
        content: '  Verses 8:5-32 are numbered 8:1-28 in Hebrew text.  '
    - title: 
      content: 'So Aaron raised his hand over the waters of Egypt, and frogs came
        up and covered the whole land! '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But the magicians were able to do the same thing with their magic.
        They, too, caused frogs to come up on the land of Egypt.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Pharaoh summoned Moses and Aaron and begged, \u201CPlead with
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> to take the frogs away from me and my people.
        I will let your people go, so they can offer sacrifices to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CYou set the time!\u201D Moses replied. \u201CTell me when you
        want me to pray for you, your officials, and your people. Then you and your
        houses will be rid of the frogs. They will remain only in the Nile River.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CDo it tomorrow,\u201D Pharaoh said.\u201CAll right,\u201D Moses
        replied, \u201Cit will be as you have said. Then you will know that there
        is no one like the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> our God. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The frogs will leave you and your houses, your officials, and your
        people. They will remain only in the Nile River.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So Moses and Aaron left Pharaoh\u2019s palace, and Moses cried out
        to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> about the frogs he had inflicted on Pharaoh. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> did just what Moses had predicted.
        The frogs in the houses, the courtyards, and the fields all died. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The Egyptians piled them into great heaps, and a terrible stench
        filled the land. '
      comments: []
    - title: A Plague of Gnats
      content: 'But when Pharaoh saw that relief had come, he became stubborn.[[COMMENT(0)]]
        He refused to listen to Moses and Aaron, just as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        had predicted.  '
      comments:
      - number: '8:15 '
        content: Hebrew <b>made his heart heavy; </b>also in 8:32.
    - title: 
      content: "So the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to Moses, \u201CTell Aaron,
        \u2018Raise your staff and strike the ground. The dust will turn into swarms
        of gnats throughout the land of Egypt.\u2019\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So Moses and Aaron did just as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had
        commanded them. When Aaron raised his hand and struck the ground with his
        staff, gnats infested the entire land, covering the Egyptians and their animals.
        All the dust in the land of Egypt turned into gnats. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Pharaoh\u2019s magicians tried to do the same thing with their secret
        arts, but this time they failed. And the gnats covered everyone, people and
        animals alike.  "
      comments: []
    - title: A Plague of Flies
      content: "\u201CThis is the finger of God!\u201D the magicians exclaimed to
        Pharaoh. But Pharaoh\u2019s heart remained hard. He wouldn\u2019t listen
        to them, just as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had predicted.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> told Moses, \u201CGet up early
        in the morning and stand in Pharaoh\u2019s way as he goes down to the river.
        Say to him, \u2018This is what the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> says: Let
        my people go, so they can worship me. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'If you refuse, then I will send swarms of flies on you, your officials,
        your people, and all the houses. The Egyptian homes will be filled with flies,
        and the ground will be covered with them. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But this time I will spare the region of Goshen, where my people
        live. No flies will be found there. Then you will know that I am the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        and that I am present even in the heart of your land. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "I will make a clear distinction between[[COMMENT(0)]] my people and
        your people. This miraculous sign will happen tomorrow.\u2019\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '8:23 '
        content: As in Greek and Latin versions; Hebrew reads <b>I will set redemption
          between.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "And the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> did just as he had said. A thick
        swarm of flies filled Pharaoh\u2019s palace and the houses of his officials.
        The whole land of Egypt was thrown into chaos by the flies.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Pharaoh called for Moses and Aaron. \u201CAll right! Go ahead and
        offer sacrifices to your God,\u201D he said. \u201CBut do it here in this
        land.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But Moses replied, \u201CThat wouldn\u2019t be right. The Egyptians
        detest the sacrifices that we offer to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> our
        God. Look, if we offer our sacrifices here where the Egyptians can see us,
        they will stone us. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "We must take a three-day trip into the wilderness to offer sacrifices
        to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> our God, just as he has commanded us.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CAll right, go ahead,\u201D Pharaoh replied. \u201CI will let
        you go into the wilderness to offer sacrifices to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        your God. But don\u2019t go too far away. Now hurry and pray for me.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Moses answered, \u201CAs soon as I leave you, I will pray to the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, and tomorrow the swarms of flies will disappear
        from you and your officials and all your people. But I am warning you, Pharaoh,
        don\u2019t lie to us again and refuse to let the people go to sacrifice to
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So Moses left Pharaoh\u2019s palace and pleaded with the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        to remove all the flies. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> did as Moses asked and caused
        the swarms of flies to disappear from Pharaoh, his officials, and his people.
        Not a single fly remained. '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: A Plague against Livestock
      content: "  \u201CGo back to Pharaoh,\u201D the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        commanded Moses. \u201CTell him, \u2018This is what the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        the God of the Hebrews, says: Let my people go, so they can worship me. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'If you continue to hold them and refuse to let them go, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "the hand of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> will strike all your
        livestock\u2014your horses, donkeys, camels, cattle, sheep, and goats\u2014with
        a deadly plague. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> will again make a distinction
        between the livestock of the Israelites and that of the Egyptians. Not a
        single one of Israel\u2019s animals will die! "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> has already set the time for the
        plague to begin. He has declared that he will strike the land tomorrow.\u2019\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> did just as he had said. The
        next morning all the livestock of the Egyptians died, but the Israelites
        didn\u2019t lose a single animal. "
      comments: []
    - title: A Plague of Festering Boils
      content: "Pharaoh sent his officials to investigate, and they discovered that
        the Israelites had not lost a single animal! But even so, Pharaoh\u2019s
        heart remained stubborn,[[COMMENT(0)]] and he still refused to let the people
        go.  "
      comments:
      - number: '9:7 '
        content: Hebrew <b>heavy.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to Moses and Aaron, \u201CTake
        handfuls of soot from a brick kiln, and have Moses toss it into the air while
        Pharaoh watches. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The ashes will spread like fine dust over the whole land of Egypt,
        causing festering boils to break out on people and animals throughout the
        land.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So they took soot from a brick kiln and went and stood before Pharaoh.
        As Pharaoh watched, Moses threw the soot into the air, and boils broke out
        on people and animals alike. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Even the magicians were unable to stand before Moses, because the
        boils had broken out on them and all the Egyptians. '
      comments: []
    - title: A Plague of Hail
      content: "But the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> hardened Pharaoh\u2019s heart,
        and just as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had predicted to Moses, Pharaoh
        refused to listen.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to Moses, \u201CGet up
        early in the morning and stand before Pharaoh. Tell him, \u2018This is what
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the God of the Hebrews, says: Let my people
        go, so they can worship me. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "If you don\u2019t, I will send more plagues on you[[COMMENT(0)]]
        and your officials and your people. Then you will know that there is no one
        like me in all the earth. "
      comments:
      - number: '9:14 '
        content: Hebrew <b>on your heart.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'By now I could have lifted my hand and struck you and your people
        with a plague to wipe you off the face of the earth. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But I have spared you for a purpose\u2014to show you my power[[COMMENT(0)]]
        and to spread my fame throughout the earth. "
      comments:
      - number: '9:16 '
        content: Greek version reads <b>to display my power in you; </b>compare Rom
          9:17.
    - title: 
      content: 'But you still lord it over my people and refuse to let them go. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So tomorrow at this time I will send a hailstorm more devastating
        than any in all the history of Egypt. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Quick! Order your livestock and servants to come in from the fields
        to find shelter. Any person or animal left outside will die when the hail
        falls.\u2019\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Some of Pharaoh\u2019s officials were afraid because of what the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had said. They quickly brought their servants
        and livestock in from the fields. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But those who paid no attention to the word of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        left theirs out in the open.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to Moses, \u201CLift your
        hand toward the sky so hail may fall on the people, the livestock, and all
        the plants throughout the land of Egypt.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So Moses lifted his staff toward the sky, and the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        sent thunder and hail, and lightning flashed toward the earth. The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        sent a tremendous hailstorm against all the land of Egypt. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Never in all the history of Egypt had there been a storm like that,
        with such devastating hail and continuous lightning. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "It left all of Egypt in ruins. The hail struck down everything in
        the open field\u2014people, animals, and plants alike. Even the trees were
        destroyed. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The only place without hail was the region of Goshen, where the people
        of Israel lived.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Pharaoh quickly summoned Moses and Aaron. \u201CThis time I
        have sinned,\u201D he confessed. \u201CThe <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> is
        the righteous one, and my people and I are wrong. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Please beg the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> to end this terrifying
        thunder and hail. We\u2019ve had enough. I will let you go; you don\u2019t
        need to stay any longer.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CAll right,\u201D Moses replied. \u201CAs soon as I leave the
        city, I will lift my hands and pray to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. Then
        the thunder and hail will stop, and you will know that the earth belongs
        to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But I know that you and your officials still do not fear the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        God.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: '(All the flax and barley were ruined by the hail, because the barley
        had formed heads and the flax was budding. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But the wheat and the emmer wheat were spared, because they had not
        yet sprouted from the ground.)  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So Moses left Pharaoh\u2019s court and went out of the city. When
        he lifted his hands to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the thunder and hail
        stopped, and the downpour ceased. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But when Pharaoh saw that the rain, hail, and thunder had stopped,
        he and his officials sinned again, and Pharaoh again became stubborn.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '9:34 '
        content: Hebrew <b>made his heart heavy.</b>
  - verses:
    - title: A Plague of Locusts
      content: "  Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to Moses, \u201CReturn
        to Pharaoh and make your demands again. I have made him and his officials
        stubborn[[COMMENT(0)]] so I can display my miraculous signs among them. "
      comments:
      - number: '10:1 '
        content: "Hebrew <b>have made his heart and his officials\u2019 hearts heavy.</b>"
    - title: 
      content: "I\u2019ve also done it so you can tell your children and grandchildren
        about how I made a mockery of the Egyptians and about the signs I displayed
        among them\u2014and so you will know that I am the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So Moses and Aaron went to Pharaoh and said, \u201CThis is what the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the God of the Hebrews, says: How long will
        you refuse to submit to me? Let my people go, so they can worship me. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'If you refuse, watch out! For tomorrow I will bring a swarm of locusts
        on your country. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "They will cover the land so that you won\u2019t be able to see the
        ground. They will devour what little is left of your crops after the hailstorm,
        including all the trees growing in the fields. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "They will overrun your palaces and the homes of your officials and
        all the houses in Egypt. Never in the history of Egypt have your ancestors
        seen a plague like this one!\u201D And with that, Moses turned and left Pharaoh.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Pharaoh\u2019s officials now came to Pharaoh and appealed to him.
        \u201CHow long will you let this man hold us hostage? Let the men go to worship
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> their God! Don\u2019t you realize that Egypt
        lies in ruins?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So Moses and Aaron were brought back to Pharaoh. \u201CAll right,\u201D
        he told them, \u201Cgo and worship the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> your God.
        But who exactly will be going with you?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Moses replied, \u201CWe will all go\u2014young and old, our sons
        and daughters, and our flocks and herds. We must all join together in celebrating
        a festival to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Pharaoh retorted, \u201CThe <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> will certainly
        need to be with you if I let you take your little ones! I can see through
        your evil plan. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Never! Only the men may go and worship the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        since that is what you requested.\u201D And Pharaoh threw them out of the
        palace.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to Moses, \u201CRaise your
        hand over the land of Egypt to bring on the locusts. Let them cover the land
        and devour every plant that survived the hailstorm.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So Moses raised his staff over Egypt, and the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        caused an east wind to blow over the land all that day and through the night.
        When morning arrived, the east wind had brought the locusts. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And the locusts swarmed over the whole land of Egypt, settling in
        dense swarms from one end of the country to the other. It was the worst locust
        plague in Egyptian history, and there has never been another one like it. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'For the locusts covered the whole country and darkened the land.
        They devoured every plant in the fields and all the fruit on the trees that
        had survived the hailstorm. Not a single leaf was left on the trees and plants
        throughout the land of Egypt.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Pharaoh quickly summoned Moses and Aaron. \u201CI have sinned against
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> your God and against you,\u201D he confessed. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CForgive my sin, just this once, and plead with the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        your God to take away this death from me.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So Moses left Pharaoh\u2019s court and pleaded with the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> responded by shifting the wind, and
        the strong west wind blew the locusts into the Red Sea.[[COMMENT(0)]] Not
        a single locust remained in all the land of Egypt. '
      comments:
      - number: '10:19 '
        content: Hebrew <b>sea of reeds.</b>
    - title: A Plague of Darkness
      content: "But the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> hardened Pharaoh\u2019s heart
        again, so he refused to let the people go.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to Moses, \u201CLift your
        hand toward heaven, and the land of Egypt will be covered with a darkness
        so thick you can feel it.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So Moses lifted his hand to the sky, and a deep darkness covered
        the entire land of Egypt for three days. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'During all that time the people could not see each other, and no
        one moved. But there was light as usual where the people of Israel lived.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Finally, Pharaoh called for Moses. \u201CGo and worship the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,\u201D
        he said. \u201CBut leave your flocks and herds here. You may even take your
        little ones with you.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CNo,\u201D Moses said, \u201Cyou must provide us with animals
        for sacrifices and burnt offerings to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> our
        God. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "All our livestock must go with us, too; not a hoof can be left behind.
        We must choose our sacrifices for the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> our God
        from among these animals. And we won\u2019t know how we are to worship the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> until we get there.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> hardened Pharaoh\u2019s heart
        once more, and he would not let them go. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CGet out of here!\u201D Pharaoh shouted at Moses. \u201CI\u2019m
        warning you. Never come back to see me again! The day you see my face, you
        will die!\u201D  "
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: "Death for Egypt\u2019s Firstborn"
      content: "  Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to Moses, \u201CI will
        strike Pharaoh and the land of Egypt with one more blow. After that, Pharaoh
        will let you leave this country. In fact, he will be so eager to get rid
        of you that he will force you all to leave. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Tell all the Israelite men and women to ask their Egyptian neighbors
        for articles of silver and gold.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "(Now the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had caused the Egyptians to
        look favorably on the people of Israel. And Moses was considered a very great
        man in the land of Egypt, respected by Pharaoh\u2019s officials and the Egyptian
        people alike.)  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Moses had announced to Pharaoh, \u201CThis is what the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        says: At midnight tonight I will pass through the heart of Egypt. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'All the firstborn sons will die in every family in Egypt, from the
        oldest son of Pharaoh, who sits on his throne, to the oldest son of his lowliest
        servant girl who grinds the flour. Even the firstborn of all the livestock
        will die. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then a loud wail will rise throughout the land of Egypt, a wail like
        no one has heard before or will ever hear again. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But among the Israelites it will be so peaceful that not even a dog
        will bark. Then you will know that the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> makes
        a distinction between the Egyptians and the Israelites. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "All the officials of Egypt will run to me and fall to the ground
        before me. \u2018Please leave!\u2019 they will beg. \u2018Hurry! And take
        all your followers with you.\u2019 Only then will I go!\u201D Then, burning
        with anger, Moses left Pharaoh.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Now the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had told Moses earlier, \u201CPharaoh
        will not listen to you, but then I will do even more mighty miracles in the
        land of Egypt.\u201D "
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: The First Passover
      content: '  While the Israelites were still in the land of Egypt, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        gave the following instructions to Moses and Aaron: '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CFrom now on, this month will be the first month of the year
        for you. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Announce to the whole community of Israel that on the tenth day of
        this month each family must choose a lamb or a young goat for a sacrifice,
        one animal for each household. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'If a family is too small to eat a whole animal, let them share with
        another family in the neighborhood. Divide the animal according to the size
        of each family and how much they can eat. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The animal you select must be a one-year-old male, either a sheep
        or a goat, with no defects.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CTake special care of this chosen animal until the evening of
        the fourteenth day of this first month. Then the whole assembly of the community
        of Israel must slaughter their lamb or young goat at twilight. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They are to take some of the blood and smear it on the sides and
        top of the doorframes of the houses where they eat the animal. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'That same night they must roast the meat over a fire and eat it along
        with bitter salad greens and bread made without yeast. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Do not eat any of the meat raw or boiled in water. The whole animal\u2014including
        the head, legs, and internal organs\u2014must be roasted over a fire. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Do not leave any of it until the next morning. Burn whatever is not
        eaten before morning.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThese are your instructions for eating this meal: Be fully
        dressed,[[COMMENT(0)]] wear your sandals, and carry your walking stick in
        your hand. Eat the meal with urgency, for this is the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        Passover. "
      comments:
      - number: '12:11 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Bind up your loins.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'On that night I will pass through the land of Egypt and strike down
        every firstborn son and firstborn male animal in the land of Egypt. I will
        execute judgment against all the gods of Egypt, for I am the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>! '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But the blood on your doorposts will serve as a sign, marking the
        houses where you are staying. When I see the blood, I will pass over you.
        This plague of death will not touch you when I strike the land of Egypt.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThis is a day to remember. Each year, from generation to generation,
        you must celebrate it as a special festival to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.
        This is a law for all time. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'For seven days the bread you eat must be made without yeast. On the
        first day of the festival, remove every trace of yeast from your homes. Anyone
        who eats bread made with yeast during the seven days of the festival will
        be cut off from the community of Israel. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'On the first day of the festival and again on the seventh day, all
        the people must observe an official day for holy assembly. No work of any
        kind may be done on these days except in the preparation of food.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CCelebrate this Festival of Unleavened Bread, for it will remind
        you that I brought your forces out of the land of Egypt on this very day.
        This festival will be a permanent law for you; celebrate this day from generation
        to generation. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The bread you eat must be made without yeast from the evening of
        the fourteenth day of the first month until the evening of the twenty-first
        day of that month. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'During those seven days, there must be no trace of yeast in your
        homes. Anyone who eats anything made with yeast during this week will be
        cut off from the community of Israel. These regulations apply both to the
        foreigners living among you and to the native-born Israelites. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "During those days you must not eat anything made with yeast. Wherever
        you live, eat only bread made without yeast.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Moses called all the elders of Israel together and said to them,
        \u201CGo, pick out a lamb or young goat for each of your families, and slaughter
        the Passover animal. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Drain the blood into a basin. Then take a bundle of hyssop branches
        and dip it into the blood. Brush the hyssop across the top and sides of the
        doorframes of your houses. And no one may go out through the door until morning. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'For the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> will pass through the land to
        strike down the Egyptians. But when he sees the blood on the top and sides
        of the doorframe, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> will pass over your home.
        He will not permit his death angel to enter your house and strike you down.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CRemember, these instructions are a permanent law that you and
        your descendants must observe forever. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When you enter the land the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> has promised
        to give you, you will continue to observe this ceremony. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then your children will ask, \u2018What does this ceremony mean?\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And you will reply, \u2018It is the Passover sacrifice to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        for he passed over the houses of the Israelites in Egypt. And though he struck
        the Egyptians, he spared our families.\u2019\u201D When Moses had finished
        speaking, all the people bowed down to the ground and worshiped.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So the people of Israel did just as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        had commanded through Moses and Aaron. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And that night at midnight, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> struck
        down all the firstborn sons in the land of Egypt, from the firstborn son
        of Pharaoh, who sat on his throne, to the firstborn son of the prisoner in
        the dungeon. Even the firstborn of their livestock were killed. '
      comments: []
    - title: "Israel\u2019s Exodus from Egypt"
      content: 'Pharaoh and all his officials and all the people of Egypt woke up
        during the night, and loud wailing was heard throughout the land of Egypt.
        There was not a single house where someone had not died.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Pharaoh sent for Moses and Aaron during the night. \u201CGet out!\u201D
        he ordered. \u201CLeave my people\u2014and take the rest of the Israelites
        with you! Go and worship the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> as you have requested. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Take your flocks and herds, as you said, and be gone. Go, but bless
        me as you leave.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "All the Egyptians urged the people of Israel to get out of the land
        as quickly as possible, for they thought, \u201CWe will all die!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The Israelites took their bread dough before yeast was added. They
        wrapped their kneading boards in their cloaks and carried them on their shoulders. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And the people of Israel did as Moses had instructed; they asked
        the Egyptians for clothing and articles of silver and gold. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> caused the Egyptians to look favorably
        on the Israelites, and they gave the Israelites whatever they asked for.
        So they stripped the Egyptians of their wealth!  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'That night the people of Israel left Rameses and started for Succoth.
        There were about 600,000 men,[[COMMENT(0)]] plus all the women and children. '
      comments:
      - number: '12:37 '
        content: Or <b>fighting men; </b>Hebrew reads <b>men on foot.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'A rabble of non-Israelites went with them, along with great flocks
        and herds of livestock. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'For bread they baked flat cakes from the dough without yeast they
        had brought from Egypt. It was made without yeast because the people were
        driven out of Egypt in such a hurry that they had no time to prepare the
        bread or other food.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The people of Israel had lived in Egypt[[COMMENT(0)]] for 430 years. '
      comments:
      - number: '12:40 '
        content: Samaritan Pentateuch reads <b>in Canaan and Egypt; </b>Greek version
          reads <b>in Egypt and Canaan.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "In fact, it was on the last day of the 430th year that all the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        forces left the land. "
      comments: []
    - title: Instructions for the Passover
      content: 'On this night the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> kept his promise to
        bring his people out of the land of Egypt. So this night belongs to him,
        and it must be commemorated every year by all the Israelites, from generation
        to generation.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to Moses and Aaron, \u201CThese
        are the instructions for the festival of Passover. No outsiders are allowed
        to eat the Passover meal. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But any slave who has been purchased may eat it if he has been circumcised. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Temporary residents and hired servants may not eat it. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Each Passover lamb must be eaten in one house. Do not carry any of
        its meat outside, and do not break any of its bones. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The whole community of Israel must celebrate this Passover festival.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CIf there are foreigners living among you who want to celebrate
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s Passover, let all their males be circumcised.
        Only then may they celebrate the Passover with you like any native-born Israelite.
        But no uncircumcised male may ever eat the Passover meal. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "This instruction applies to everyone, whether a native-born Israelite
        or a foreigner living among you.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So all the people of Israel followed all the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        commands to Moses and Aaron. "
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Dedication of the Firstborn
      content: '  Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to Moses, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CDedicate to me every firstborn among the Israelites. The first
        offspring to be born, of both humans and animals, belongs to me.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So Moses said to the people, \u201CThis is a day to remember forever\u2014the
        day you left Egypt, the place of your slavery. Today the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        has brought you out by the power of his mighty hand. (Remember, eat no food
        containing yeast.) "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'On this day in early spring, in the month of Abib,[[COMMENT(0)]]
        you have been set free. '
      comments:
      - number: '13:4 '
        content: Hebrew <b>On this day in the month of Abib. </b>This first month
          of the ancient Hebrew lunar calendar usually occurs within the months of
          March and April.
    - title: 
      content: "You must celebrate this event in this month each year after the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        brings you into the land of the Canaanites, Hittites, Amorites, Hivites,
        and Jebusites. (He swore to your ancestors that he would give you this land\u2014a
        land flowing with milk and honey.) "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'For seven days the bread you eat must be made without yeast. Then
        on the seventh day, celebrate a feast to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Eat bread without yeast during those seven days. In fact, there must
        be no yeast bread or any yeast at all found within the borders of your land
        during this time.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201COn the seventh day you must explain to your children, \u2018I
        am celebrating what the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> did for me when I left
        Egypt.\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "This annual festival will be a visible sign to you, like a mark branded
        on your hand or your forehead. Let it remind you always to recite this teaching
        of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>: \u2018With a strong hand, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        rescued you from Egypt.\u2019[[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>  "
      comments:
      - number: '13:9 '
        content: Or <b>Let it remind you always to keep the instructions of the <span
          class="ChapterContent_nd__ECPAf">Lord</span> on the tip of your tongue,
          because with a strong hand, the <span class="ChapterContent_nd__ECPAf">Lord</span>
          rescued you from Egypt.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'So observe the decree of this festival at the appointed time each
        year.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThis is what you must do when the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        fulfills the promise he swore to you and to your ancestors. When he gives
        you the land where the Canaanites now live, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'you must present all firstborn sons and firstborn male animals to
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, for they belong to him. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'A firstborn donkey may be bought back from the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        by presenting a lamb or young goat in its place. But if you do not buy it
        back, you must break its neck. However, you must buy back every firstborn
        son.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CAnd in the future, your children will ask you, \u2018What does
        all this mean?\u2019 Then you will tell them, \u2018With the power of his
        mighty hand, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> brought us out of Egypt, the
        place of our slavery. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Pharaoh stubbornly refused to let us go, so the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        killed all the firstborn males throughout the land of Egypt, both people
        and animals. That is why I now sacrifice all the firstborn males to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2014except
        that the firstborn sons are always bought back.\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - title: "Israel\u2019s Wilderness Detour"
      content: "This ceremony will be like a mark branded on your hand or your forehead.
        It is a reminder that the power of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        mighty hand brought us out of Egypt.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When Pharaoh finally let the people go, God did not lead them along
        the main road that runs through Philistine territory, even though that was
        the shortest route to the Promised Land. God said, \u201CIf the people are
        faced with a battle, they might change their minds and return to Egypt.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So God led them in a roundabout way through the wilderness toward
        the Red Sea.[[COMMENT(0)]] Thus the Israelites left Egypt like an army ready
        for battle.[[COMMENT(1)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '13:18a '
        content: Hebrew <b>sea of reeds.</b>
      - number: '13:18b '
        content: Greek version reads <b>left Egypt in the fifth generation.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "Moses took the bones of Joseph with him, for Joseph had made the
        sons of Israel swear to do this. He said, \u201CGod will certainly come to
        help you. When he does, you must take my bones with you from this place.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The Israelites left Succoth and camped at Etham on the edge of the
        wilderness. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> went ahead of them. He guided them
        during the day with a pillar of cloud, and he provided light at night with
        a pillar of fire. This allowed them to travel by day or by night. '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: 
      content: '  Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> gave these instructions to
        Moses: '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201COrder the Israelites to turn back and camp by Pi-hahiroth between
        Migdol and the sea. Camp there along the shore, across from Baal-zephon. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Pharaoh will think, \u2018The Israelites are confused. They
        are trapped in the wilderness!\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - title: The Egyptians Pursue Israel
      content: "And once again I will harden Pharaoh\u2019s heart, and he will chase
        after you.[[COMMENT(0)]] I have planned this in order to display my glory
        through Pharaoh and his whole army. After this the Egyptians will know that
        I am the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>!\u201D So the Israelites camped there
        as they were told.  "
      comments:
      - number: '14:4 '
        content: Hebrew <b>after them.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "When word reached the king of Egypt that the Israelites had fled,
        Pharaoh and his officials changed their minds. \u201CWhat have we done, letting
        all those Israelite slaves get away?\u201D they asked. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So Pharaoh harnessed his chariot and called up his troops. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He took with him 600 of Egypt\u2019s best chariots, along with the
        rest of the chariots of Egypt, each with its commander. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> hardened the heart of Pharaoh, the
        king of Egypt, so he chased after the people of Israel, who had left with
        fists raised in defiance. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The Egyptians chased after them with all the forces in Pharaoh\u2019s
        army\u2014all his horses and chariots, his charioteers, and his troops. The
        Egyptians caught up with the people of Israel as they were camped beside
        the shore near Pi-hahiroth, across from Baal-zephon.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'As Pharaoh approached, the people of Israel looked up and panicked
        when they saw the Egyptians overtaking them. They cried out to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "and they said to Moses, \u201CWhy did you bring us out here to die
        in the wilderness? Weren\u2019t there enough graves for us in Egypt? What
        have you done to us? Why did you make us leave Egypt? "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Didn\u2019t we tell you this would happen while we were still in
        Egypt? We said, \u2018Leave us alone! Let us be slaves to the Egyptians.
        It\u2019s better to be a slave in Egypt than a corpse in the wilderness!\u2019\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But Moses told the people, \u201CDon\u2019t be afraid. Just stand
        still and watch the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> rescue you today. The Egyptians
        you see today will never be seen again. "
      comments: []
    - title: Escape through the Red Sea
      content: "The <smallcaps>Lord </smallcaps>himself will fight for you. Just
        stay calm.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to Moses, \u201CWhy are
        you crying out to me? Tell the people to get moving! "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Pick up your staff and raise your hand over the sea. Divide the water
        so the Israelites can walk through the middle of the sea on dry ground. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And I will harden the hearts of the Egyptians, and they will charge
        in after the Israelites. My great glory will be displayed through Pharaoh
        and his troops, his chariots, and his charioteers. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When my glory is displayed through them, all Egypt will see my glory
        and know that I am the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then the angel of God, who had been leading the people of Israel,
        moved to the rear of the camp. The pillar of cloud also moved from the front
        and stood behind them. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The cloud settled between the Egyptian and Israelite camps. As darkness
        fell, the cloud turned to fire, lighting up the night. But the Egyptians
        and Israelites did not approach each other all night.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then Moses raised his hand over the sea, and the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        opened up a path through the water with a strong east wind. The wind blew
        all that night, turning the seabed into dry land. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So the people of Israel walked through the middle of the sea on dry
        ground, with walls of water on each side!  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then the Egyptians\u2014all of Pharaoh\u2019s horses, chariots, and
        charioteers\u2014chased them into the middle of the sea. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But just before dawn the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> looked down
        on the Egyptian army from the pillar of fire and cloud, and he threw their
        forces into total confusion. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He twisted[[COMMENT(0)]] their chariot wheels, making their chariots
        difficult to drive. \u201CLet\u2019s get out of here\u2014away from these
        Israelites!\u201D the Egyptians shouted. \u201CThe <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        is fighting for them against Egypt!\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '14:25 '
        content: As in Greek version, Samaritan Pentateuch, and Syriac version; Hebrew
          reads <b>He removed.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "When all the Israelites had reached the other side, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        said to Moses, \u201CRaise your hand over the sea again. Then the waters
        will rush back and cover the Egyptians and their chariots and charioteers.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So as the sun began to rise, Moses raised his hand over the sea,
        and the water rushed back into its usual place. The Egyptians tried to escape,
        but the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> swept them into the sea. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then the waters returned and covered all the chariots and charioteers\u2014the
        entire army of Pharaoh. Of all the Egyptians who had chased the Israelites
        into the sea, not a single one survived.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But the people of Israel had walked through the middle of the sea
        on dry ground, as the water stood up like a wall on both sides. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'That is how the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> rescued Israel from the
        hand of the Egyptians that day. And the Israelites saw the bodies of the
        Egyptians washed up on the seashore. '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: A Song of Deliverance
      content: "  Then Moses and the people of Israel sang this song to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>:\u201CI
        will sing to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,for he has triumphed gloriously;he
        has hurled both horse and riderinto the sea.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> is my strength and my song;he has
        given me victory.This is my God, and I will praise him\u2014my father\u2019s
        God, and I will exalt him!  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> is a warrior;Yahweh[[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>
        is his name!</smallcaps>  '
      comments:
      - number: '15:3 '
        content: "<b>Yahweh </b>is a transliteration of the proper name <b>YHWH </b>that
          is sometimes rendered \u201CJehovah\u201D; in this translation it is usually
          rendered \u201Cthe <span class=\"ChapterContent_nd__ECPAf\">Lord</span>\u201D
          (note the use of small capitals)."
    - title: 
      content: "Pharaoh\u2019s chariots and armyhe has hurled into the sea.The finest
        of Pharaoh\u2019s officersare drowned in the Red Sea.[[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '15:4 '
        content: Hebrew <b>sea of reeds; </b>also in 15:22.
    - title: 
      content: 'The deep waters gushed over them;they sank to the bottom like a stone.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CYour right hand, O <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,is glorious
        in power.Your right hand, O <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,smashes the enemy.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'In the greatness of your majesty,you overthrow those who rise against
        you.You unleash your blazing fury;it consumes them like straw.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'At the blast of your breath,the waters piled up!The surging waters
        stood straight like a wall;in the heart of the sea the deep waters became
        hard.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThe enemy boasted, \u2018I will chase themand catch up with
        them.I will plunder themand consume them.I will flash my sword;my powerful
        hand will destroy them.\u2019  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But you blew with your breath,and the sea covered them.They sank
        like leadin the mighty waters.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWho is like you among the gods, O <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2014glorious
        in holiness,awesome in splendor,performing great wonders?  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'You raised your right hand,and the earth swallowed our enemies.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWith your unfailing love you leadthe people you have redeemed.In
        your might, you guide themto your sacred home.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The peoples hear and tremble;anguish grips those who live in Philistia.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The leaders of Edom are terrified;the nobles of Moab tremble.All
        who live in Canaan melt away;  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'terror and dread fall upon them.The power of your armmakes them lifeless
        as stoneuntil your people pass by, O <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,until the
        people you purchased pass by.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "You will bring them in and plant them on your own mountain\u2014the
        place, O <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, reserved for your own dwelling,the
        sanctuary, O Lord, that your hands have established.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> will reign forever and ever!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When Pharaoh\u2019s horses, chariots, and charioteers rushed into
        the sea, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> brought the water crashing down
        on them. But the people of Israel had walked through the middle of the sea
        on dry ground!  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Miriam the prophet, Aaron\u2019s sister, took a tambourine and
        led all the women as they played their tambourines and danced. "
      comments: []
    - title: Bitter Water at Marah
      content: "And Miriam sang this song:\u201CSing to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,for
        he has triumphed gloriously;he has hurled both horse and riderinto the sea.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then Moses led the people of Israel away from the Red Sea, and they
        moved out into the desert of Shur. They traveled in this desert for three
        days without finding any water. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When they came to the oasis of Marah, the water was too bitter to
        drink. So they called the place Marah (which means \u201Cbitter\u201D).  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then the people complained and turned against Moses. \u201CWhat are
        we going to drink?\u201D they demanded. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So Moses cried out to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> for help, and
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> showed him a piece of wood. Moses threw it
        into the water, and this made the water good to drink.It was there at Marah
        that the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> set before them the following decree
        as a standard to test their faithfulness to him. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He said, \u201CIf you will listen carefully to the voice of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        your God and do what is right in his sight, obeying his commands and keeping
        all his decrees, then I will not make you suffer any of the diseases I sent
        on the Egyptians; for I am the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> who heals you.\u201D  "
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Manna and Quail from Heaven
      content: '  Then the whole community of Israel set out from Elim and journeyed
        into the wilderness of Sin,[[COMMENT(0)]] between Elim and Mount Sinai. They
        arrived there on the fifteenth day of the second month, one month after leaving
        the land of Egypt.[[COMMENT(1)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '16:1a '
        content: The geographical name <b>Sin </b>is related to <b>Sinai </b>and
          should not be confused with the English word <b>sin.</b>
      - number: '16:1b '
        content: The Exodus had occurred on the fifteenth day of the first month
          (see Num 33:3).
    - title: 
      content: 'There, too, the whole community of Israel complained about Moses
        and Aaron.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CIf only the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had killed us back
        in Egypt,\u201D they moaned. \u201CThere we sat around pots filled with meat
        and ate all the bread we wanted. But now you have brought us into this wilderness
        to starve us all to death.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to Moses, \u201CLook, I\u2019m
        going to rain down food from heaven for you. Each day the people can go out
        and pick up as much food as they need for that day. I will test them in this
        to see whether or not they will follow my instructions. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "On the sixth day they will gather food, and when they prepare it,
        there will be twice as much as usual.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So Moses and Aaron said to all the people of Israel, \u201CBy evening
        you will realize it was the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> who brought you out
        of the land of Egypt. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "In the morning you will see the glory of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        because he has heard your complaints, which are against him, not against
        us. What have we done that you should complain about us?\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Moses added, \u201CThe <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> will give
        you meat to eat in the evening and bread to satisfy you in the morning, for
        he has heard all your complaints against him. What have we done? Yes, your
        complaints are against the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, not against us.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Moses said to Aaron, \u201CAnnounce this to the entire community
        of Israel: \u2018Present yourselves before the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        for he has heard your complaining.\u2019\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And as Aaron spoke to the whole community of Israel, they looked
        out toward the wilderness. There they could see the awesome glory of the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> in the cloud.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to Moses, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CI have heard the Israelites\u2019 complaints. Now tell them,
        \u2018In the evening you will have meat to eat, and in the morning you will
        have all the bread you want. Then you will know that I am the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        your God.\u2019\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'That evening vast numbers of quail flew in and covered the camp.
        And the next morning the area around the camp was wet with dew. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When the dew evaporated, a flaky substance as fine as frost blanketed
        the ground. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The Israelites were puzzled when they saw it. \u201CWhat is it?\u201D
        they asked each other. They had no idea what it was.And Moses told them,
        \u201CIt is the food the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> has given you to eat. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "These are the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s instructions: Each
        household should gather as much as it needs. Pick up two quarts[[COMMENT(0)]]
        for each person in your tent.\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '16:16 '
        content: Hebrew <b>1 omer </b>[2.2 liters]; also in 16:32, 33.
    - title: 
      content: 'So the people of Israel did as they were told. Some gathered a lot,
        some only a little. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But when they measured it out,[[COMMENT(0)]] everyone had just enough.
        Those who gathered a lot had nothing left over, and those who gathered only
        a little had enough. Each family had just what it needed.  '
      comments:
      - number: '16:18 '
        content: Hebrew <b>measured it with an omer.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "Then Moses told them, \u201CDo not keep any of it until morning.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But some of them didn\u2019t listen and kept some of it until morning.
        But by then it was full of maggots and had a terrible smell. Moses was very
        angry with them.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'After this the people gathered the food morning by morning, each
        family according to its need. And as the sun became hot, the flakes they
        had not picked up melted and disappeared. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "On the sixth day, they gathered twice as much as usual\u2014four
        quarts[[COMMENT(0)]] for each person instead of two. Then all the leaders
        of the community came and asked Moses for an explanation. "
      comments:
      - number: '16:22 '
        content: Hebrew <b>2 omers </b>[4.4 liters].
    - title: 
      content: "He told them, \u201CThis is what the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        commanded: Tomorrow will be a day of complete rest, a holy Sabbath day set
        apart for the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. So bake or boil as much as you
        want today, and set aside what is left for tomorrow.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So they put some aside until morning, just as Moses had commanded.
        And in the morning the leftover food was wholesome and good, without maggots
        or odor. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Moses said, \u201CEat this food today, for today is a Sabbath day
        dedicated to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. There will be no food on the
        ground today. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "You may gather the food for six days, but the seventh day is the
        Sabbath. There will be no food on the ground that day.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Some of the people went out anyway on the seventh day, but they found
        no food. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> asked Moses, \u201CHow long will
        these people refuse to obey my commands and instructions? "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "They must realize that the Sabbath is the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        gift to you. That is why he gives you a two-day supply on the sixth day,
        so there will be enough for two days. On the Sabbath day you must each stay
        in your place. Do not go out to pick up food on the seventh day.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So the people did not gather any food on the seventh day.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The Israelites called the food manna.[[COMMENT(0)]] It was white
        like coriander seed, and it tasted like honey wafers.  '
      comments:
      - number: '16:31 '
        content: "<b>Manna </b>means \u201CWhat is it?\u201D See 16:15."
    - title: 
      content: "Then Moses said, \u201CThis is what the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        has commanded: Fill a two-quart container with manna to preserve it for your
        descendants. Then later generations will be able to see the food I gave you
        in the wilderness when I set you free from Egypt.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Moses said to Aaron, \u201CGet a jar and fill it with two quarts
        of manna. Then put it in a sacred place before the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        to preserve it for all future generations.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Aaron did just as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had commanded Moses.
        He eventually placed it in the Ark of the Covenant\u2014in front of the stone
        tablets inscribed with the terms of the covenant.[[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '16:34 '
        content: Hebrew <b>He placed it in front of the Testimony; </b>see note on
          25:16.
    - title: 
      content: 'So the people of Israel ate manna for forty years until they arrived
        at the land where they would settle. They ate manna until they came to the
        border of the land of Canaan.  '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Water from the Rock
      content: "  At the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s command, the whole community
        of Israel left the wilderness of Sin[[COMMENT(0)]] and moved from place to
        place. Eventually they camped at Rephidim, but there was no water there for
        the people to drink. "
      comments:
      - number: '17:1 '
        content: The geographical name <b>Sin </b>is related to <b>Sinai </b>and
          should not be confused with the English word <b>sin.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "So once more the people complained against Moses. \u201CGive us water
        to drink!\u201D they demanded.\u201CQuiet!\u201D Moses replied. \u201CWhy
        are you complaining against me? And why are you testing the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But tormented by thirst, they continued to argue with Moses. \u201CWhy
        did you bring us out of Egypt? Are you trying to kill us, our children, and
        our livestock with thirst?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Moses cried out to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, \u201CWhat
        should I do with these people? They are ready to stone me!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to Moses, \u201CWalk out in
        front of the people. Take your staff, the one you used when you struck the
        water of the Nile, and call some of the elders of Israel to join you. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "I will stand before you on the rock at Mount Sinai.[[COMMENT(0)]]
        Strike the rock, and water will come gushing out. Then the people will be
        able to drink.\u201D So Moses struck the rock as he was told, and water gushed
        out as the elders looked on.  "
      comments:
      - number: '17:6 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Horeb, </b>another name for Sinai.
    - title: Israel Defeats the Amalekites
      content: "Moses named the place Massah (which means \u201Ctest\u201D) and Meribah
        (which means \u201Carguing\u201D) because the people of Israel argued with
        Moses and tested the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> by saying, \u201CIs the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> here with us or not?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'While the people of Israel were still at Rephidim, the warriors of
        Amalek attacked them. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Moses commanded Joshua, \u201CChoose some men to go out and fight
        the army of Amalek for us. Tomorrow, I will stand at the top of the hill,
        holding the staff of God in my hand.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So Joshua did what Moses had commanded and fought the army of Amalek.
        Meanwhile, Moses, Aaron, and Hur climbed to the top of a nearby hill. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'As long as Moses held up the staff in his hand, the Israelites had
        the advantage. But whenever he dropped his hand, the Amalekites gained the
        advantage. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Moses\u2019 arms soon became so tired he could no longer hold them
        up. So Aaron and Hur found a stone for him to sit on. Then they stood on
        each side of Moses, holding up his hands. So his hands held steady until
        sunset. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'As a result, Joshua overwhelmed the army of Amalek in battle.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "After the victory, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> instructed Moses,
        \u201CWrite this down on a scroll as a permanent reminder, and read it aloud
        to Joshua: I will erase the memory of Amalek from under heaven.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Moses built an altar there and named it Yahweh-Nissi (which means
        \u201Cthe <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> is my banner\u201D). "
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: "Jethro\u2019s Visit to Moses"
      content: "  Moses\u2019 father-in-law, Jethro, the priest of Midian, heard
        about everything God had done for Moses and his people, the Israelites. He
        heard especially about how the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had rescued them
        from Egypt.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Earlier, Moses had sent his wife, Zipporah, and his two sons back
        to Jethro, who had taken them in. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "(Moses\u2019 first son was named Gershom,[[COMMENT(0)]] for Moses
        had said when the boy was born, \u201CI have been a foreigner in a foreign
        land.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: '18:3 '
        content: "<b>Gershom </b>sounds like a Hebrew term that means \u201Ca foreigner
          there.\u201D"
    - title: 
      content: "His second son was named Eliezer,[[COMMENT(0)]] for Moses had said,
        \u201CThe God of my ancestors was my helper; he rescued me from the sword
        of Pharaoh.\u201D) "
      comments:
      - number: '18:4 '
        content: "<b>Eliezer </b>means \u201CGod is my helper.\u201D"
    - title: 
      content: "Jethro, Moses\u2019 father-in-law, now came to visit Moses in the
        wilderness. He brought Moses\u2019 wife and two sons with him, and they arrived
        while Moses and the people were camped near the mountain of God. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Jethro had sent a message to Moses, saying, \u201CI, Jethro, your
        father-in-law, am coming to see you with your wife and your two sons.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So Moses went out to meet his father-in-law. He bowed low and kissed
        him. They asked about each other\u2019s welfare and then went into Moses\u2019
        tent. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Moses told his father-in-law everything the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        had done to Pharaoh and Egypt on behalf of Israel. He also told about all
        the hardships they had experienced along the way and how the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        had rescued his people from all their troubles. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Jethro was delighted when he heard about all the good things the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had done for Israel as he rescued them from the
        hand of the Egyptians.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CPraise the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,\u201D Jethro said,
        \u201Cfor he has rescued you from the Egyptians and from Pharaoh. Yes, he
        has rescued Israel from the powerful hand of Egypt! "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "I know now that the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> is greater than all
        other gods, because he rescued his people from the oppression of the proud
        Egyptians.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: "Jethro\u2019s Wise Advice"
      content: "Then Jethro, Moses\u2019 father-in-law, brought a burnt offering
        and sacrifices to God. Aaron and all the elders of Israel came out and joined
        him in a sacrificial meal in God\u2019s presence.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The next day, Moses took his seat to hear the people\u2019s disputes
        against each other. They waited before him from morning till evening.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When Moses\u2019 father-in-law saw all that Moses was doing for the
        people, he asked, \u201CWhat are you really accomplishing here? Why are you
        trying to do all this alone while everyone stands around you from morning
        till evening?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Moses replied, \u201CBecause the people come to me to get a ruling
        from God. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When a dispute arises, they come to me, and I am the one who settles
        the case between the quarreling parties. I inform the people of God\u2019s
        decrees and give them his instructions.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThis is not good!\u201D Moses\u2019 father-in-law exclaimed. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CYou\u2019re going to wear yourself out\u2014and the people,
        too. This job is too heavy a burden for you to handle all by yourself. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Now listen to me, and let me give you a word of advice, and may God
        be with you. You should continue to be the people\u2019s representative before
        God, bringing their disputes to him. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Teach them God\u2019s decrees, and give them his instructions. Show
        them how to conduct their lives. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But select from all the people some capable, honest men who fear
        God and hate bribes. Appoint them as leaders over groups of one thousand,
        one hundred, fifty, and ten. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "They should always be available to solve the people\u2019s common
        disputes, but have them bring the major cases to you. Let the leaders decide
        the smaller matters themselves. They will help you carry the load, making
        the task easier for you. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "If you follow this advice, and if God commands you to do so, then
        you will be able to endure the pressures, and all these people will go home
        in peace.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Moses listened to his father-in-law\u2019s advice and followed his
        suggestions. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He chose capable men from all over Israel and appointed them as leaders
        over the people. He put them in charge of groups of one thousand, one hundred,
        fifty, and ten. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "These men were always available to solve the people\u2019s common
        disputes. They brought the major cases to Moses, but they took care of the
        smaller matters themselves.  "
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> Reveals Himself at Sinai
      content: '  Exactly two months after the Israelites left Egypt,[[COMMENT(0)]]
        they arrived in the wilderness of Sinai. '
      comments:
      - number: '19:1 '
        content: Hebrew <b>In the third month after the Israelites left Egypt, on
          the very day, </b>i.e., two lunar months to the day after leaving Egypt.
          Compare Num 33:3.
    - title: 
      content: 'After breaking camp at Rephidim, they came to the wilderness of Sinai
        and set up camp there at the base of Mount Sinai.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Moses climbed the mountain to appear before God. The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        called to him from the mountain and said, \u201CGive these instructions to
        the family of Jacob; announce it to the descendants of Israel: "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u2018You have seen what I did to the Egyptians. You know how I carried
        you on eagles\u2019 wings and brought you to myself. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Now if you will obey me and keep my covenant, you will be my own
        special treasure from among all the peoples on earth; for all the earth belongs
        to me. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And you will be my kingdom of priests, my holy nation.\u2019 This
        is the message you must give to the people of Israel.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So Moses returned from the mountain and called together the elders
        of the people and told them everything the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had
        commanded him. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And all the people responded together, \u201CWe will do everything
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> has commanded.\u201D So Moses brought the
        people\u2019s answer back to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to Moses, \u201CI will
        come to you in a thick cloud, Moses, so the people themselves can hear me
        when I speak with you. Then they will always trust you.\u201DMoses told the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> what the people had said. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> told Moses, \u201CGo down and
        prepare the people for my arrival. Consecrate them today and tomorrow, and
        have them wash their clothing. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Be sure they are ready on the third day, for on that day the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        will come down on Mount Sinai as all the people watch. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Mark off a boundary all around the mountain. Warn the people, \u2018Be
        careful! Do not go up on the mountain or even touch its boundaries. Anyone
        who touches the mountain will certainly be put to death. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "No hand may touch the person or animal that crosses the boundary;
        instead, stone them or shoot them with arrows. They must be put to death.\u2019
        However, when the ram\u2019s horn sounds a long blast, then the people may
        go up on the mountain.[[COMMENT(0)]]\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '19:13 '
        content: Or <b>up to the mountain.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'So Moses went down to the people. He consecrated them for worship,
        and they washed their clothes. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He told them, \u201CGet ready for the third day, and until then abstain
        from having sexual intercourse.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "On the morning of the third day, thunder roared and lightning flashed,
        and a dense cloud came down on the mountain. There was a long, loud blast
        from a ram\u2019s horn, and all the people trembled. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Moses led them out from the camp to meet with God, and they stood
        at the foot of the mountain. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'All of Mount Sinai was covered with smoke because the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        had descended on it in the form of fire. The smoke billowed into the sky
        like smoke from a brick kiln, and the whole mountain shook violently. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "As the blast of the ram\u2019s horn grew louder and louder, Moses
        spoke, and God thundered his reply. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> came down on the top of Mount Sinai
        and called Moses to the top of the mountain. So Moses climbed the mountain.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> told Moses, \u201CGo back down
        and warn the people not to break through the boundaries to see the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        or they will die. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Even the priests who regularly come near to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        must purify themselves so that the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> does not break
        out and destroy them.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CBut <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,\u201D Moses protested, \u201Cthe
        people cannot come up to Mount Sinai. You already warned us. You told me,
        \u2018Mark off a boundary all around the mountain to set it apart as holy.\u2019\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said, \u201CGo down and bring
        Aaron back up with you. In the meantime, do not let the priests or the people
        break through to approach the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, or he will break
        out and destroy them.\u201D  "
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Ten Commandments for the Covenant Community
      content: '  Then God gave the people all these instructions[[COMMENT(0)]]:  '
      comments:
      - number: '20:1 '
        content: Hebrew <b>all these words.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CI am the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> your God, who rescued
        you from the land of Egypt, the place of your slavery.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CYou must not have any other god but me.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CYou must not make for yourself an idol of any kind or an image
        of anything in the heavens or on the earth or in the sea. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "You must not bow down to them or worship them, for I, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        your God, am a jealous God who will not tolerate your affection for any other
        gods. I lay the sins of the parents upon their children; the entire family
        is affected\u2014even children in the third and fourth generations of those
        who reject me. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But I lavish unfailing love for a thousand generations on those[[COMMENT(0)]]
        who love me and obey my commands.  '
      comments:
      - number: '20:6 '
        content: Hebrew <b>for thousands of those.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CYou must not misuse the name of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        your God. The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> will not let you go unpunished
        if you misuse his name.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CRemember to observe the Sabbath day by keeping it holy. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'You have six days each week for your ordinary work, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'but the seventh day is a Sabbath day of rest dedicated to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        your God. On that day no one in your household may do any work. This includes
        you, your sons and daughters, your male and female servants, your livestock,
        and any foreigners living among you. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'For in six days the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> made the heavens,
        the earth, the sea, and everything in them; but on the seventh day he rested.
        That is why the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> blessed the Sabbath day and set
        it apart as holy.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CHonor your father and mother. Then you will live a long, full
        life in the land the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> your God is giving you.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CYou must not murder.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CYou must not commit adultery.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CYou must not steal.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CYou must not testify falsely against your neighbor.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CYou must not covet your neighbor\u2019s house. You must not
        covet your neighbor\u2019s wife, male or female servant, ox or donkey, or
        anything else that belongs to your neighbor.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When the people heard the thunder and the loud blast of the ram\u2019s
        horn, and when they saw the flashes of lightning and the smoke billowing
        from the mountain, they stood at a distance, trembling with fear.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And they said to Moses, \u201CYou speak to us, and we will listen.
        But don\u2019t let God speak directly to us, or we will die!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CDon\u2019t be afraid,\u201D Moses answered them, \u201Cfor
        God has come in this way to test you, and so that your fear of him will keep
        you from sinning!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: Proper Use of Altars
      content: 'As the people stood in the distance, Moses approached the dark cloud
        where God was.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to Moses, \u201CSay this
        to the people of Israel: You saw for yourselves that I spoke to you from
        heaven. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Remember, you must not make any idols of silver or gold to rival
        me.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CBuild for me an altar made of earth, and offer your sacrifices
        to me\u2014your burnt offerings and peace offerings, your sheep and goats,
        and your cattle. Build my altar wherever I cause my name to be remembered,
        and I will come to you and bless you. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'If you use stones to build my altar, use only natural, uncut stones.
        Do not shape the stones with a tool, for that would make the altar unfit
        for holy use. '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Fair Treatment of Slaves
      content: "  \u201CThese are the regulations you must present to Israel.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CIf you buy a Hebrew slave, he may serve for no more than six
        years. Set him free in the seventh year, and he will owe you nothing for
        his freedom. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'If he was single when he became your slave, he shall leave single.
        But if he was married before he became a slave, then his wife must be freed
        with him.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CIf his master gave him a wife while he was a slave and they
        had sons or daughters, then only the man will be free in the seventh year,
        but his wife and children will still belong to his master. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But the slave may declare, \u2018I love my master, my wife, and my
        children. I don\u2019t want to go free.\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'If he does this, his master must present him before God.[[COMMENT(0)]]
        Then his master must take him to the door or doorpost and publicly pierce
        his ear with an awl. After that, the slave will serve his master for life.  '
      comments:
      - number: '21:6 '
        content: Or <b>before the judges.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWhen a man sells his daughter as a slave, she will not be freed
        at the end of six years as the men are. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'If she does not satisfy her owner, he must allow her to be bought
        back again. But he is not allowed to sell her to foreigners, since he is
        the one who broke the contract with her. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But if the slave\u2019s owner arranges for her to marry his son,
        he may no longer treat her as a slave but as a daughter.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CIf a man who has married a slave wife takes another wife for
        himself, he must not neglect the rights of the first wife to food, clothing,
        and sexual intimacy. "
      comments: []
    - title: Cases of Personal Injury
      content: 'If he fails in any of these three obligations, she may leave as a
        free woman without making any payment.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CAnyone who assaults and kills another person must be put to
        death. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But if it was simply an accident permitted by God, I will appoint
        a place of refuge where the slayer can run for safety. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'However, if someone deliberately kills another person, then the slayer
        must be dragged even from my altar and be put to death.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CAnyone who strikes father or mother must be put to death.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CKidnappers must be put to death, whether they are caught in
        possession of their victims or have already sold them as slaves.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CAnyone who dishonors[[COMMENT(0)]] father or mother must be
        put to death.  "
      comments:
      - number: '21:17 '
        content: Greek version reads <b>Anyone who speaks disrespectfully of. </b>Compare
          Matt 15:4; Mark 7:10.
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CNow suppose two men quarrel, and one hits the other with a
        stone or fist, and the injured person does not die but is confined to bed. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'If he is later able to walk outside again, even with a crutch, the
        assailant will not be punished but must compensate his victim for lost wages
        and provide for his full recovery.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CIf a man beats his male or female slave with a club and the
        slave dies as a result, the owner must be punished. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But if the slave recovers within a day or two, then the owner shall
        not be punished, since the slave is his property.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CNow suppose two men are fighting, and in the process they accidentally
        strike a pregnant woman so she gives birth prematurely.[[COMMENT(0)]] If
        no further injury results, the man who struck the woman must pay the amount
        of compensation the woman\u2019s husband demands and the judges approve. "
      comments:
      - number: '21:22 '
        content: Or <b>so she has a miscarriage; </b>Hebrew reads <b>so her children
          come out.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'But if there is further injury, the punishment must match the injury:
        a life for a life, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'an eye for an eye, a tooth for a tooth, a hand for a hand, a foot
        for a foot, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'a burn for a burn, a wound for a wound, a bruise for a bruise.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CIf a man hits his male or female slave in the eye and the eye
        is blinded, he must let the slave go free to compensate for the eye. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And if a man knocks out the tooth of his male or female slave, he
        must let the slave go free to compensate for the tooth.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CIf an ox[[COMMENT(0)]] gores a man or woman to death, the ox
        must be stoned, and its flesh may not be eaten. In such a case, however,
        the owner will not be held liable. "
      comments:
      - number: '21:28 '
        content: Or <b>bull, </b>or <b>cow; </b>also in 21:29-36.
    - title: 
      content: 'But suppose the ox had a reputation for goring, and the owner had
        been informed but failed to keep it under control. If the ox then kills someone,
        it must be stoned, and the owner must also be put to death. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "However, the dead person\u2019s relatives may accept payment to compensate
        for the loss of life. The owner of the ox may redeem his life by paying whatever
        is demanded.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThe same regulation applies if the ox gores a boy or a girl. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But if the ox gores a slave, either male or female, the animal\u2019s
        owner must pay the slave\u2019s owner thirty silver coins,[[COMMENT(0)]]
        and the ox must be stoned.  "
      comments:
      - number: '21:32 '
        content: Hebrew <b>30 shekels of silver, </b>about 12 ounces or 342 grams
          in weight.
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CSuppose someone digs or uncovers a pit and fails to cover it,
        and then an ox or a donkey falls into it. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The owner of the pit must pay full compensation to the owner of the
        animal, but then he gets to keep the dead animal.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CIf someone\u2019s ox injures a neighbor\u2019s ox and the injured
        ox dies, then the two owners must sell the live ox and divide the price equally
        between them. They must also divide the dead animal. "
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Protection of Property
      content: "    [[COMMENT(0)]]\u201CIf someone steals an ox[[COMMENT(1)]] or
        sheep and then kills or sells it, the thief must pay back five oxen for each
        ox stolen, and four sheep for each sheep stolen.  "
      comments:
      - number: '22:1a '
        content: '  Verse 22:1 is numbered 21:37 in Hebrew text.  '
      - number: '22:1b '
        content: 'Or <b>bull, </b>or <b>cow; </b>also in 22:4, 9, 10.  '
    - title: 
      content: "  [[COMMENT(0)]]\u201CIf a thief is caught in the act of breaking
        into a house and is struck and killed in the process, the person who killed
        the thief is not guilty of murder. "
      comments:
      - number: '22:2 '
        content: '  Verses 22:2-31 are numbered 22:1-30 in Hebrew text.  '
    - title: 
      content: "But if it happens in daylight, the one who killed the thief is guilty
        of murder.\u201CA thief who is caught must pay in full for everything he
        stole. If he cannot pay, he must be sold as a slave to pay for his theft. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "If someone steals an ox or a donkey or a sheep and it is found in
        the thief\u2019s possession, then the thief must pay double the value of
        the stolen animal.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CIf an animal is grazing in a field or vineyard and the owner
        lets it stray into someone else\u2019s field to graze, then the animal\u2019s
        owner must pay compensation from the best of his own grain or grapes.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CIf you are burning thornbushes and the fire gets out of control
        and spreads into another person\u2019s field, destroying the sheaves or the
        uncut grain or the whole crop, the one who started the fire must pay for
        the lost crop.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CSuppose someone leaves money or goods with a neighbor for safekeeping,
        and they are stolen from the neighbor\u2019s house. If the thief is caught,
        the compensation is double the value of what was stolen. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But if the thief is not caught, the neighbor must appear before God,[[COMMENT(0)]]
        who will determine if he stole the property.  '
      comments:
      - number: '22:8 '
        content: Or <b>before the judges.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CSuppose there is a dispute between two people who both claim
        to own a particular ox, donkey, sheep, article of clothing, or any lost property.
        Both parties must come before God, and the person whom God declares[[COMMENT(0)]]
        guilty must pay double compensation to the other.  "
      comments:
      - number: '22:9 '
        content: Or <b>before the judges, and the person whom the judges declare.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CNow suppose someone leaves a donkey, ox, sheep, or any other
        animal with a neighbor for safekeeping, but it dies or is injured or is taken
        away, and no one sees what happened. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The neighbor must then take an oath in the presence of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.
        If the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> confirms that the neighbor did not steal
        the property, the owner must accept the verdict, and no payment will be required. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But if the animal was indeed stolen, the guilty person must pay compensation
        to the owner. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'If it was torn to pieces by a wild animal, the remains of the carcass
        must be shown as evidence, and no compensation will be required.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CIf someone borrows an animal from a neighbor and it is injured
        or dies when the owner is absent, the person who borrowed it must pay full
        compensation. "
      comments: []
    - title: Social Responsibility
      content: 'But if the owner was present, no compensation is required. And no
        compensation is required if the animal was rented, for this loss is covered
        by the rental fee.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CIf a man seduces a virgin who is not engaged to anyone and
        has sex with her, he must pay the customary bride price and marry her. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But if her father refuses to let him marry her, the man must still
        pay him an amount equal to the bride price of a virgin.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CYou must not allow a sorceress to live.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CAnyone who has sexual relations with an animal must certainly
        be put to death.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CAnyone who sacrifices to any god other than the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        must be destroyed.[[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>  </smallcaps>"
      comments:
      - number: '22:20 '
        content: The Hebrew term used here refers to the complete consecration of
          things or people to the <span class="ChapterContent_nd__ECPAf">Lord</span>,
          either by destroying them or by giving them as an offering.
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CYou must not mistreat or oppress foreigners in any way. Remember,
        you yourselves were once foreigners in the land of Egypt.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CYou must not exploit a widow or an orphan. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'If you exploit them in any way and they cry out to me, then I will
        certainly hear their cry. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'My anger will blaze against you, and I will kill you with the sword.
        Then your wives will be widows and your children fatherless.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CIf you lend money to any of my people who are in need, do not
        charge interest as a money lender would. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "If you take your neighbor\u2019s cloak as security for a loan, you
        must return it before sunset. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'This coat may be the only blanket your neighbor has. How can a person
        sleep without it? If you do not return it and your neighbor cries out to
        me for help, then I will hear, for I am merciful.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CYou must not dishonor God or curse any of your rulers.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CYou must not hold anything back when you give me offerings
        from your crops and your wine.\u201CYou must give me your firstborn sons.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CYou must also give me the firstborn of your cattle, sheep,
        and goats. But leave the newborn animal with its mother for seven days; then
        give it to me on the eighth day.  "
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: A Call for Justice
      content: "  \u201CYou must not pass along false rumors. You must not cooperate
        with evil people by lying on the witness stand.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CYou must not follow the crowd in doing wrong. When you are
        called to testify in a dispute, do not be swayed by the crowd to twist justice. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And do not slant your testimony in favor of a person just because
        that person is poor.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CIf you come upon your enemy\u2019s ox or donkey that has strayed
        away, take it back to its owner. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'If you see that the donkey of someone who hates you has collapsed
        under its load, do not walk by. Instead, stop and help.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CIn a lawsuit, you must not deny justice to the poor.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CBe sure never to charge anyone falsely with evil. Never sentence
        an innocent or blameless person to death, for I never declare a guilty person
        to be innocent.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CTake no bribes, for a bribe makes you ignore something that
        you clearly see. A bribe makes even a righteous person twist the truth.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CYou must not oppress foreigners. You know what it\u2019s like
        to be a foreigner, for you yourselves were once foreigners in the land of
        Egypt.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CPlant and harvest your crops for six years, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'but let the land be renewed and lie uncultivated during the seventh
        year. Then let the poor among you harvest whatever grows on its own. Leave
        the rest for wild animals to eat. The same applies to your vineyards and
        olive groves.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CYou have six days each week for your ordinary work, but on
        the seventh day you must stop working. This gives your ox and your donkey
        a chance to rest. It also allows your slaves and the foreigners living among
        you to be refreshed.  "
      comments: []
    - title: Three Annual Festivals
      content: "\u201CPay close attention to all my instructions. You must not call
        on the name of any other gods. Do not even speak their names.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CEach year you must celebrate three festivals in my honor. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'First, celebrate the Festival of Unleavened Bread. For seven days
        the bread you eat must be made without yeast, just as I commanded you. Celebrate
        this festival annually at the appointed time in early spring, in the month
        of Abib,[[COMMENT(0)]] for that is the anniversary of your departure from
        Egypt. No one may appear before me without an offering.  '
      comments:
      - number: '23:15 '
        content: Hebrew <b>appointed time in the month of Abib. </b>This first month
          of the ancient Hebrew lunar calendar usually occurs within the months of
          March and April.
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CSecond, celebrate the Festival of Harvest,[[COMMENT(0)]] when
        you bring me the first crops of your harvest.\u201CFinally, celebrate the
        Festival of the Final Harvest[[COMMENT(1)]] at the end of the harvest season,
        when you have harvested all the crops from your fields. "
      comments:
      - number: '23:16a '
        content: Or <b>Festival of Weeks. </b>This was later called the Festival
          of Pentecost (see Acts 2:1). It is celebrated today as Shavuot (or Shabuoth).
      - number: '23:16b '
        content: Or <b>Festival of Ingathering. </b>This was later called the Festival
          of Shelters or Festival of Tabernacles (see Lev 23:33-36). It is celebrated
          today as Sukkot (or Succoth).
    - title: 
      content: 'At these three times each year, every man in Israel must appear before
        the Sovereign, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CYou must not offer the blood of my sacrificial offerings together
        with any baked goods containing yeast. And do not leave the fat from the
        festival offerings until the next morning.  "
      comments: []
    - title: "A Promise of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s Presence"
      content: "\u201CAs you harvest your crops, bring the very best of the first
        harvest to the house of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> your God.\u201CYou
        must not cook a young goat in its mother\u2019s milk.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CSee, I am sending an angel before you to protect you on your
        journey and lead you safely to the place I have prepared for you. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Pay close attention to him, and obey his instructions. Do not rebel
        against him, for he is my representative, and he will not forgive your rebellion. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But if you are careful to obey him, following all my instructions,
        then I will be an enemy to your enemies, and I will oppose those who oppose
        you. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'For my angel will go before you and bring you into the land of the
        Amorites, Hittites, Perizzites, Canaanites, Hivites, and Jebusites, so you
        may live there. And I will destroy them completely. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'You must not worship the gods of these nations or serve them in any
        way or imitate their evil practices. Instead, you must utterly destroy them
        and smash their sacred pillars.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CYou must serve only the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> your God.
        If you do, I[[COMMENT(0)]] will bless you with food and water, and I will
        protect you from illness. "
      comments:
      - number: '23:25 '
        content: As in Greek and Latin versions; Hebrew reads <b>he.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'There will be no miscarriages or infertility in your land, and I
        will give you long, full lives.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CI will send my terror ahead of you and create panic among all
        the people whose lands you invade. I will make all your enemies turn and
        run. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I will send terror[[COMMENT(0)]] ahead of you to drive out the Hivites,
        Canaanites, and Hittites. '
      comments:
      - number: '23:28 '
        content: Often rendered <b>the hornet. </b>The meaning of the Hebrew is uncertain.
    - title: 
      content: 'But I will not drive them out in a single year, because the land
        would become desolate and the wild animals would multiply and threaten you. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I will drive them out a little at a time until your population has
        increased enough to take possession of the land. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And I will fix your boundaries from the Red Sea to the Mediterranean
        Sea,[[COMMENT(0)]] and from the eastern wilderness to the Euphrates River.[[COMMENT(1)]]
        I will hand over to you the people now living in the land, and you will drive
        them out ahead of you.  '
      comments:
      - number: '23:31a '
        content: Hebrew <b>from the sea of reeds to the sea of the Philistines.</b>
      - number: '23:31b '
        content: Hebrew <b>from the wilderness to the river.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CMake no treaties with them or their gods. "
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: "Israel Accepts the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s Covenant"
      content: "  Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> instructed Moses: \u201CCome
        up here to me, and bring along Aaron, Nadab, Abihu, and seventy of Israel\u2019s
        elders. All of you must worship from a distance. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Only Moses is allowed to come near to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.
        The others must not come near, and none of the other people are allowed to
        climb up the mountain with him.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Moses went down to the people and repeated all the instructions
        and regulations the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had given him. All the people
        answered with one voice, \u201CWe will do everything the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        has commanded.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Moses carefully wrote down all the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        instructions. Early the next morning Moses got up and built an altar at the
        foot of the mountain. He also set up twelve pillars, one for each of the
        twelve tribes of Israel. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then he sent some of the young Israelite men to present burnt offerings
        and to sacrifice bulls as peace offerings to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Moses drained half the blood from these animals into basins. The
        other half he splattered against the altar.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then he took the Book of the Covenant and read it aloud to the people.
        Again they all responded, \u201CWe will do everything the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        has commanded. We will obey.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Moses took the blood from the basins and splattered it over
        the people, declaring, \u201CLook, this blood confirms the covenant the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        has made with you in giving you these instructions.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then Moses, Aaron, Nadab, Abihu, and the seventy elders of Israel
        climbed up the mountain. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'There they saw the God of Israel. Under his feet there seemed to
        be a surface of brilliant blue lapis lazuli, as clear as the sky itself. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And though these nobles of Israel gazed upon God, he did not destroy
        them. In fact, they ate a covenant meal, eating and drinking in his presence!  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to Moses, \u201CCome up
        to me on the mountain. Stay there, and I will give you the tablets of stone
        on which I have inscribed the instructions and commands so you can teach
        the people.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So Moses and his assistant Joshua set out, and Moses climbed up the
        mountain of God.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Moses told the elders, \u201CStay here and wait for us until we come
        back. Aaron and Hur are here with you. If anyone has a dispute while I am
        gone, consult with them.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then Moses climbed up the mountain, and the cloud covered it. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And the glory of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> settled down on
        Mount Sinai, and the cloud covered it for six days. On the seventh day the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> called to Moses from inside the cloud. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'To the Israelites at the foot of the mountain, the glory of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        appeared at the summit like a consuming fire. '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Offerings for the Tabernacle
      content: '  The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to Moses, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CTell the people of Israel to bring me their sacred offerings.
        Accept the contributions from all whose hearts are moved to offer them. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Here is a list of sacred offerings you may accept from them:gold,
        silver, and bronze;  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'blue, purple, and scarlet thread;fine linen and goat hair for cloth;  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'tanned ram skins and fine goatskin leather;acacia wood;  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'olive oil for the lamps;spices for the anointing oil and the fragrant
        incense;  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "onyx stones, and other gemstones to be set in the ephod and the priest\u2019s
        chestpiece.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CHave the people of Israel build me a holy sanctuary so I can
        live among them. "
      comments: []
    - title: Plans for the Ark of the Covenant
      content: 'You must build this Tabernacle and its furnishings exactly according
        to the pattern I will show you.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CHave the people make an Ark of acacia wood\u2014a sacred chest
        45 inches long, 27 inches wide, and 27 inches high.[[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '25:10 '
        content: Hebrew <b>2.5 cubits </b>[115 centimeters] <b>long, 1.5 cubits </b>[69
          centimeters] <b>wide, and 1.5 cubits high.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'Overlay it inside and outside with pure gold, and run a molding of
        gold all around it. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Cast four gold rings and attach them to its four feet, two rings
        on each side. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Make poles from acacia wood, and overlay them with gold. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Insert the poles into the rings at the sides of the Ark to carry
        it. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'These carrying poles must stay inside the rings; never remove them. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When the Ark is finished, place inside it the stone tablets inscribed
        with the terms of the covenant,[[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps> which I will give
        to you.</smallcaps>  '
      comments:
      - number: '25:16 '
        content: "Hebrew <b>Place inside the Ark the Testimony; </b>similarly in
          25:21. The Hebrew word for \u201Ctestimony\u201D refers to the terms of
          the <span class=\"ChapterContent_nd__ECPAf\">Lord</span>\u2019s covenant
          with Israel as written on stone tablets, and also to the covenant itself."
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThen make the Ark\u2019s cover\u2014the place of atonement\u2014from
        pure gold. It must be 45 inches long and 27 inches wide.[[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '25:17 '
        content: Hebrew <b>2.5 cubits </b>[115 centimeters] <b>long and 1.5 cubits
          </b>[69 centimeters] <b>wide.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'Then make two cherubim from hammered gold, and place them on the
        two ends of the atonement cover. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Mold the cherubim on each end of the atonement cover, making it all
        of one piece of gold. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The cherubim will face each other and look down on the atonement
        cover. With their wings spread above it, they will protect it. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Place inside the Ark the stone tablets inscribed with the terms of
        the covenant, which I will give to you. Then put the atonement cover on top
        of the Ark. '
      comments: []
    - title: Plans for the Table
      content: 'I will meet with you there and talk to you from above the atonement
        cover between the gold cherubim that hover over the Ark of the Covenant.[[COMMENT(0)]]
        From there I will give you my commands for the people of Israel.  '
      comments:
      - number: '25:22 '
        content: Or <b>Ark of the Testimony.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThen make a table of acacia wood, 36 inches long, 18 inches
        wide, and 27 inches high.[[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '25:23 '
        content: Hebrew <b>2 cubits </b>[92 centimeters] <b>long, 1 cubit </b>[46
          centimeters] <b>wide, and 1.5 cubits </b>[69 centimeters] <b>high.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'Overlay it with pure gold and run a gold molding around the edge. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Decorate it with a 3-inch border[[COMMENT(0)]] all around, and run
        a gold molding along the border. '
      comments:
      - number: '25:25 '
        content: Hebrew <b>a border of a handbreadth </b>[8 centimeters].
    - title: 
      content: 'Make four gold rings for the table and attach them at the four corners
        next to the four legs. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Attach the rings near the border to hold the poles that are used
        to carry the table. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Make these poles from acacia wood, and overlay them with gold. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Make special containers of pure gold for the table\u2014bowls, ladles,
        pitchers, and jars\u2014to be used in pouring out liquid offerings. "
      comments: []
    - title: Plans for the Lampstand
      content: 'Place the Bread of the Presence on the table to remain before me
        at all times.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CMake a lampstand of pure, hammered gold. Make the entire lampstand
        and its decorations of one piece\u2014the base, center stem, lamp cups, buds,
        and petals. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Make it with six branches going out from the center stem, three on
        each side. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Each of the six branches will have three lamp cups shaped like almond
        blossoms, complete with buds and petals. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Craft the center stem of the lampstand with four lamp cups shaped
        like almond blossoms, complete with buds and petals. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'There will also be an almond bud beneath each pair of branches where
        the six branches extend from the center stem. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The almond buds and branches must all be of one piece with the center
        stem, and they must be hammered from pure gold. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then make the seven lamps for the lampstand, and set them so they
        reflect their light forward. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The lamp snuffers and trays must also be made of pure gold. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'You will need 75 pounds[[COMMENT(0)]] of pure gold for the lampstand
        and its accessories.  '
      comments:
      - number: '25:39 '
        content: Hebrew <b>1 talent </b>[34 kilograms].
  - verses:
    - title: Plans for the Tabernacle
      content: "  \u201CMake the Tabernacle from ten curtains of finely woven linen.
        Decorate the curtains with blue, purple, and scarlet thread and with skillfully
        embroidered cherubim. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "These ten curtains must all be exactly the same size\u201442 feet
        long and 6 feet wide.[[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '26:2 '
        content: Hebrew <b>28 cubits </b>[12.9 meters] <b>long and 4 cubits </b>[1.8
          meters] <b>wide.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'Join five of these curtains together to make one long curtain, then
        join the other five into a second long curtain. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Put loops of blue yarn along the edge of the last curtain in each
        set. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The fifty loops along the edge of one curtain are to match the fifty
        loops along the edge of the other curtain. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then make fifty gold clasps and fasten the long curtains together
        with the clasps. In this way, the Tabernacle will be made of one continuous
        piece.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CMake eleven curtains of goat-hair cloth to serve as a tent
        covering for the Tabernacle. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "These eleven curtains must all be exactly the same size\u201445 feet
        long and 6 feet wide.[[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '26:8 '
        content: Hebrew <b>30 cubits </b>[13.8 meters] <b>long and 4 cubits </b>[1.8
          meters] <b>wide.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'Join five of these curtains together to make one long curtain, and
        join the other six into a second long curtain. Allow 3 feet of material from
        the second set of curtains to hang over the front[[COMMENT(0)]] of the sacred
        tent. '
      comments:
      - number: '26:9 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Double over the sixth sheet at the front.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'Make fifty loops for one edge of each large curtain. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then make fifty bronze clasps, and fasten the loops of the long curtains
        with the clasps. In this way, the tent covering will be made of one continuous
        piece. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The remaining 3 feet[[COMMENT(0)]] of this tent covering will be
        left to hang over the back of the Tabernacle. '
      comments:
      - number: '26:12 '
        content: Hebrew <b>The half sheet that is left over.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'Allow 18 inches[[COMMENT(0)]] of remaining material to hang down
        over each side, so the Tabernacle is completely covered. '
      comments:
      - number: '26:13 '
        content: Hebrew <b>1 cubit </b>[46 centimeters].
    - title: 
      content: 'Complete the tent covering with a protective layer of tanned ram
        skins and a layer of fine goatskin leather.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CFor the framework of the Tabernacle, construct frames of acacia
        wood. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Each frame must be 15 feet high and 27 inches wide,[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '26:16 '
        content: Hebrew <b>10 cubits </b>[4.6 meters] <b>high and 1.5 cubits </b>[69
          centimeters] <b>wide.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'with two pegs under each frame. Make all the frames identical. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Make twenty of these frames to support the curtains on the south
        side of the Tabernacle. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Also make forty silver bases\u2014two bases under each frame, with
        the pegs fitting securely into the bases. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'For the north side of the Tabernacle, make another twenty frames, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'with their forty silver bases, two bases under each frame. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Make six frames for the rear\u2014the west side of the Tabernacle\u2014 "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'along with two additional frames to reinforce the rear corners of
        the Tabernacle. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'These corner frames will be matched at the bottom and firmly attached
        at the top with a single ring, forming a single corner unit. Make both of
        these corner units the same way. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So there will be eight frames at the rear of the Tabernacle, set
        in sixteen silver bases\u2014two bases under each frame.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CMake crossbars of acacia wood to link the frames, five crossbars
        for the north side of the Tabernacle "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'and five for the south side. Also make five crossbars for the rear
        of the Tabernacle, which will face west. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The middle crossbar, attached halfway up the frames, will run all
        the way from one end of the Tabernacle to the other. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Overlay the frames with gold, and make gold rings to hold the crossbars.
        Overlay the crossbars with gold as well.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CSet up this Tabernacle according to the pattern you were shown
        on the mountain.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CFor the inside of the Tabernacle, make a special curtain of
        finely woven linen. Decorate it with blue, purple, and scarlet thread and
        with skillfully embroidered cherubim. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Hang this curtain on gold hooks attached to four posts of acacia
        wood. Overlay the posts with gold, and set them in four silver bases. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Hang the inner curtain from clasps, and put the Ark of the Covenant[[COMMENT(0)]]
        in the room behind it. This curtain will separate the Holy Place from the
        Most Holy Place.  '
      comments:
      - number: '26:33 '
        content: Or <b>Ark of the Testimony; </b>also in 26:34.
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThen put the Ark\u2019s cover\u2014the place of atonement\u2014on
        top of the Ark of the Covenant inside the Most Holy Place. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Place the table outside the inner curtain on the north side of the
        Tabernacle, and place the lampstand across the room on the south side.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CMake another curtain for the entrance to the sacred tent. Make
        it of finely woven linen and embroider it with exquisite designs, using blue,
        purple, and scarlet thread. "
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Plans for the Altar of Burnt Offering
      content: "  \u201CUsing acacia wood, construct a square altar 7-1/2 feet wide,
        7-1/2 feet long, and 4-1/2 feet high.[[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '27:1 '
        content: Hebrew <b>5 cubits </b>[2.3 meters] <b>wide, 5 cubits long, a square,
          and 3 cubits </b>[1.4 meters] <b>high.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'Make horns for each of its four corners so that the horns and altar
        are all one piece. Overlay the altar with bronze. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Make ash buckets, shovels, basins, meat forks, and firepans, all
        of bronze. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Make a bronze grating for it, and attach four bronze rings at its
        four corners. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Install the grating halfway down the side of the altar, under the
        ledge. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'For carrying the altar, make poles from acacia wood, and overlay
        them with bronze. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Insert the poles through the rings on the two sides of the altar. '
      comments: []
    - title: Plans for the Courtyard
      content: 'The altar must be hollow, made from planks. Build it just as you
        were shown on the mountain.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThen make the courtyard for the Tabernacle, enclosed with curtains
        made of finely woven linen. On the south side, make the curtains 150 feet
        long.[[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '27:9 '
        content: Hebrew <b>100 cubits </b>[46 meters]; also in 27:11.
    - title: 
      content: 'They will be held up by twenty posts set securely in twenty bronze
        bases. Hang the curtains with silver hooks and rings. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Make the curtains the same on the north side\u2014150 feet of curtains
        held up by twenty posts set securely in bronze bases. Hang the curtains with
        silver hooks and rings. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The curtains on the west end of the courtyard will be 75 feet long,[[COMMENT(0)]]
        supported by ten posts set into ten bases. '
      comments:
      - number: '27:12 '
        content: Hebrew <b>50 cubits </b>[23 meters]; also in 27:13.
    - title: 
      content: 'The east end of the courtyard, the front, will also be 75 feet long. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The courtyard entrance will be on the east end, flanked by two curtains.
        The curtain on the right side will be 22-1/2 feet long,[[COMMENT(0)]] supported
        by three posts set into three bases. '
      comments:
      - number: '27:14 '
        content: Hebrew <b>15 cubits </b>[6.9 meters]; also in 27:15.
    - title: 
      content: 'The curtain on the left side will also be 22-1/2 feet long, supported
        by three posts set into three bases.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CFor the entrance to the courtyard, make a curtain that is 30
        feet long.[[COMMENT(0)]] Make it from finely woven linen, and decorate it
        with beautiful embroidery in blue, purple, and scarlet thread. Support it
        with four posts, each securely set in its own base. "
      comments:
      - number: '27:16 '
        content: Hebrew <b>20 cubits </b>[9.2 meters].
    - title: 
      content: 'All the posts around the courtyard must have silver rings and hooks
        and bronze bases. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So the entire courtyard will be 150 feet long and 75 feet wide, with
        curtain walls 7-1/2 feet high,[[COMMENT(0)]] made from finely woven linen.
        The bases for the posts will be made of bronze.  '
      comments:
      - number: '27:18 '
        content: Hebrew <b>100 cubits </b>[46 meters] <b>long and 50 by 50 </b>[23
          meters] <b>wide and 5 cubits </b>[2.3 meters] <b>high.</b>
    - title: Light for the Tabernacle
      content: "\u201CAll the articles used in the rituals of the Tabernacle, including
        all the tent pegs used to support the Tabernacle and the courtyard curtains,
        must be made of bronze.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CCommand the people of Israel to bring you pure oil of pressed
        olives for the light, to keep the lamps burning continually. "
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Clothing for the Priests
      content: "  \u201CCall for your brother, Aaron, and his sons, Nadab, Abihu,
        Eleazar, and Ithamar. Set them apart from the rest of the people of Israel
        so they may minister to me and be my priests. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Make sacred garments for Aaron that are glorious and beautiful. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Instruct all the skilled craftsmen whom I have filled with the spirit
        of wisdom. Have them make garments for Aaron that will distinguish him as
        a priest set apart for my service. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'These are the garments they are to make: a chestpiece, an ephod,
        a robe, a patterned tunic, a turban, and a sash. They are to make these sacred
        garments for your brother, Aaron, and his sons to wear when they serve me
        as priests. '
      comments: []
    - title: Design of the Ephod
      content: 'So give them fine linen cloth, gold thread, and blue, purple, and
        scarlet thread.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThe craftsmen must make the ephod of finely woven linen and
        skillfully embroider it with gold and with blue, purple, and scarlet thread. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'It will consist of two pieces, front and back, joined at the shoulders
        with two shoulder-pieces. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The decorative sash will be made of the same materials: finely woven
        linen embroidered with gold and with blue, purple, and scarlet thread.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CTake two onyx stones, and engrave on them the names of the
        tribes of Israel. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Six names will be on each stone, arranged in the order of the births
        of the original sons of Israel. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Engrave these names on the two stones in the same way a jeweler engraves
        a seal. Then mount the stones in settings of gold filigree. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Fasten the two stones on the shoulder-pieces of the ephod as a reminder
        that Aaron represents the people of Israel. Aaron will carry these names
        on his shoulders as a constant reminder whenever he goes before the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Make the settings of gold filigree, '
      comments: []
    - title: Design of the Chestpiece
      content: 'then braid two cords of pure gold and attach them to the filigree
        settings on the shoulders of the ephod.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThen, with great skill and care, make a chestpiece to be worn
        for seeking a decision from God.[[COMMENT(0)]] Make it to match the ephod,
        using finely woven linen embroidered with gold and with blue, purple, and
        scarlet thread. "
      comments:
      - number: '28:15 '
        content: Hebrew <b>a chestpiece for decision.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'Make the chestpiece of a single piece of cloth folded to form a pouch
        nine inches[[COMMENT(0)]] square. '
      comments:
      - number: '28:16 '
        content: Hebrew <b>1 span </b>[23 centimeters].
    - title: 
      content: 'Mount four rows of gemstones[[COMMENT(0)]] on it. The first row will
        contain a red carnelian, a pale-green peridot, and an emerald. '
      comments:
      - number: '28:17 '
        content: The identification of some of these gemstones is uncertain.
    - title: 
      content: 'The second row will contain a turquoise, a blue lapis lazuli, and
        a white moonstone. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The third row will contain an orange jacinth, an agate, and a purple
        amethyst. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The fourth row will contain a blue-green beryl, an onyx, and a green
        jasper. All these stones will be set in gold filigree. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Each stone will represent one of the twelve sons of Israel, and the
        name of that tribe will be engraved on it like a seal.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CTo attach the chestpiece to the ephod, make braided cords of
        pure gold thread. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then make two gold rings and attach them to the top corners of the
        chestpiece. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Tie the two gold cords to the two rings on the chestpiece. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Tie the other ends of the cords to the gold settings on the shoulder-pieces
        of the ephod. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then make two more gold rings and attach them to the inside edges
        of the chestpiece next to the ephod. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And make two more gold rings and attach them to the front of the
        ephod, below the shoulder-pieces, just above the knot where the decorative
        sash is fastened to the ephod. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then attach the bottom rings of the chestpiece to the rings on the
        ephod with blue cords. This will hold the chestpiece securely to the ephod
        above the decorative sash.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CIn this way, Aaron will carry the names of the tribes of Israel
        on the sacred chestpiece[[COMMENT(0)]] over his heart when he goes into the
        Holy Place. This will be a continual reminder that he represents the people
        when he comes before the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. "
      comments:
      - number: '28:29 '
        content: Hebrew <b>the chestpiece for decision; </b>also in 28:30. See 28:15.
    - title: Additional Clothing for the Priests
      content: "Insert the Urim and Thummim into the sacred chestpiece so they will
        be carried over Aaron\u2019s heart when he goes into the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        presence. In this way, Aaron will always carry over his heart the objects
        used to determine the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s will for his people
        whenever he goes in before the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CMake the robe that is worn with the ephod from a single piece
        of blue cloth, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "with an opening for Aaron\u2019s head in the middle of it. Reinforce
        the opening with a woven collar[[COMMENT(0)]] so it will not tear. "
      comments:
      - number: '28:32 '
        content: The meaning of the Hebrew is uncertain.
    - title: 
      content: 'Make pomegranates out of blue, purple, and scarlet yarn, and attach
        them to the hem of the robe, with gold bells between them. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The gold bells and pomegranates are to alternate all around the hem. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Aaron will wear this robe whenever he ministers before the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        and the bells will tinkle as he goes in and out of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        presence in the Holy Place. If he wears it, he will not die.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CNext make a medallion of pure gold, and engrave it like a seal
        with these words: <smallcaps>Holy to the Lord</smallcaps>. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Attach the medallion with a blue cord to the front of Aaron\u2019s
        turban, where it must remain. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Aaron must wear it on his forehead so he may take on himself any
        guilt of the people of Israel when they consecrate their sacred offerings.
        He must always wear it on his forehead so the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        will accept the people.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWeave Aaron\u2019s patterned tunic from fine linen cloth. Fashion
        the turban from this linen as well. Also make a sash, and decorate it with
        colorful embroidery.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CFor Aaron\u2019s sons, make tunics, sashes, and special head
        coverings that are glorious and beautiful. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Clothe your brother, Aaron, and his sons with these garments, and
        then anoint and ordain them. Consecrate them so they can serve as my priests. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Also make linen undergarments for them, to be worn next to their
        bodies, reaching from their hips to their thighs. '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Dedication of the Priests
      content: "  \u201CThis is the ceremony you must follow when you consecrate
        Aaron and his sons to serve me as priests: Take a young bull and two rams
        with no defects. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then, using choice wheat flour and no yeast, make loaves of bread,
        thin cakes mixed with olive oil, and wafers spread with oil. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Place them all in a single basket, and present them at the entrance
        of the Tabernacle, along with the young bull and the two rams.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CPresent Aaron and his sons at the entrance of the Tabernacle,[[COMMENT(0)]]
        and wash them with water. "
      comments:
      - number: '29:4 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Tent of Meeting; </b>also in 29:10, 11, 30, 32, 42, 44.
    - title: 
      content: "Dress Aaron in his priestly garments\u2014the tunic, the robe worn
        with the ephod, the ephod itself, and the chestpiece. Then wrap the decorative
        sash of the ephod around him. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Place the turban on his head, and fasten the sacred medallion to
        the turban. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then anoint him by pouring the anointing oil over his head. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Next present his sons, and dress them in their tunics. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Wrap the sashes around the waists of Aaron and his sons, and put
        their special head coverings on them. Then the right to the priesthood will
        be theirs by law forever. In this way, you will ordain Aaron and his sons.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CBring the young bull to the entrance of the Tabernacle, where
        Aaron and his sons will lay their hands on its head. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then slaughter the bull in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        presence at the entrance of the Tabernacle. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Put some of its blood on the horns of the altar with your finger,
        and pour out the rest at the base of the altar. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Take all the fat around the internal organs, the long lobe of the
        liver, and the two kidneys and the fat around them, and burn it all on the
        altar. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then take the rest of the bull, including its hide, meat, and dung,
        and burn it outside the camp as a sin offering.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CNext Aaron and his sons must lay their hands on the head of
        one of the rams. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then slaughter the ram, and splatter its blood against all sides
        of the altar. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Cut the ram into pieces, and wash off the internal organs and the
        legs. Set them alongside the head and the other pieces of the body, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'then burn the entire animal on the altar. This is a burnt offering
        to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>; it is a pleasing aroma, a special gift
        presented to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CNow take the other ram, and have Aaron and his sons lay their
        hands on its head. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then slaughter it, and apply some of its blood to the right earlobes
        of Aaron and his sons. Also put it on the thumbs of their right hands and
        the big toes of their right feet. Splatter the rest of the blood against
        all sides of the altar. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then take some of the blood from the altar and some of the anointing
        oil, and sprinkle it on Aaron and his sons and on their garments. In this
        way, they and their garments will be set apart as holy.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CSince this is the ram for the ordination of Aaron and his sons,
        take the fat of the ram, including the fat of the broad tail, the fat around
        the internal organs, the long lobe of the liver, and the two kidneys and
        the fat around them, along with the right thigh. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then take one round loaf of bread, one thin cake mixed with olive
        oil, and one wafer from the basket of bread without yeast that was placed
        in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s presence. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Put all these in the hands of Aaron and his sons to be lifted up
        as a special offering to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Afterward take the various breads from their hands, and burn them
        on the altar along with the burnt offering. It is a pleasing aroma to the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, a special gift for him. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then take the breast of Aaron\u2019s ordination ram, and lift it
        up in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s presence as a special offering
        to him. Then keep it as your own portion.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CSet aside the portions of the ordination ram that belong to
        Aaron and his sons. This includes the breast and the thigh that were lifted
        up before the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> as a special offering. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'In the future, whenever the people of Israel lift up a peace offering,
        a portion of it must be set aside for Aaron and his descendants. This is
        their permanent right, and it is a sacred offering from the Israelites to
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CAaron\u2019s sacred garments must be preserved for his descendants
        who succeed him, and they will wear them when they are anointed and ordained. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The descendant who succeeds him as high priest will wear these clothes
        for seven days as he ministers in the Tabernacle and the Holy Place.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CTake the ram used in the ordination ceremony, and boil its
        meat in a sacred place. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then Aaron and his sons will eat this meat, along with the bread
        in the basket, at the Tabernacle entrance. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They alone may eat the meat and bread used for their purification[[COMMENT(0)]]
        in the ordination ceremony. No one else may eat them, for these things are
        set apart and holy. '
      comments:
      - number: '29:33 '
        content: Or <b>their atonement.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'If any of the ordination meat or bread remains until the morning,
        it must be burned. It may not be eaten, for it is holy.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThis is how you will ordain Aaron and his sons to their offices,
        just as I have commanded you. The ordination ceremony will go on for seven
        days. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Each day you must sacrifice a young bull as a sin offering to purify
        them, making them right with the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.[[COMMENT(0)]]
        Afterward, cleanse the altar by purifying it[[COMMENT(1)]]; make it holy
        by anointing it with oil. '
      comments:
      - number: '29:36a '
        content: Or <b>to make atonement.</b>
      - number: '29:36b '
        content: Or <b>by making atonement for it; </b>similarly in 29:37.
    - title: 
      content: 'Purify the altar, and consecrate it every day for seven days. After
        that, the altar will be absolutely holy, and whatever touches it will become
        holy.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThese are the sacrifices you are to offer regularly on the
        altar. Each day, offer two lambs that are a year old, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'one in the morning and the other in the evening. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'With one of them, offer two quarts of choice flour mixed with one
        quart of pure oil of pressed olives; also, offer one quart of wine[[COMMENT(0)]]
        as a liquid offering. '
      comments:
      - number: '29:40 '
        content: Hebrew <b>1/10 [of an ephah] </b>[2.2 liters] <b>of choice flour
          . . . 1/4 of a hin </b>[1 liter] <b>of pure oil . . . 1/4 of a hin of wine.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'Offer the other lamb in the evening, along with the same offerings
        of flour and wine as in the morning. It will be a pleasing aroma, a special
        gift presented to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThese burnt offerings are to be made each day from generation
        to generation. Offer them in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s presence
        at the Tabernacle entrance; there I will meet with you and speak with you. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I will meet the people of Israel there, in the place made holy by
        my glorious presence. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Yes, I will consecrate the Tabernacle and the altar, and I will consecrate
        Aaron and his sons to serve me as priests. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then I will live among the people of Israel and be their God, '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Plans for the Incense Altar
      content: "  \u201CThen make another altar of acacia wood for burning incense. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Make it 18 inches square and 36 inches high,[[COMMENT(0)]] with horns
        at the corners carved from the same piece of wood as the altar itself. '
      comments:
      - number: '30:2 '
        content: Hebrew <b>1 cubit </b>[46 centimeters] <b>long and 1 cubit wide,
          a square, and 2 cubits </b>[92 centimeters] <b>high.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'Overlay the top, sides, and horns of the altar with pure gold, and
        run a gold molding around the entire altar. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Make two gold rings, and attach them on opposite sides of the altar
        below the gold molding to hold the carrying poles. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Make the poles of acacia wood and overlay them with gold. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Place the incense altar just outside the inner curtain that shields
        the Ark of the Covenant,[[COMMENT(0)]] in front of the Ark\u2019s cover\u2014the
        place of atonement\u2014that covers the tablets inscribed with the terms
        of the covenant.[[COMMENT(1)]] I will meet with you there.  "
      comments:
      - number: '30:6a '
        content: Or <b>Ark of the Testimony; </b>also in 30:26.
      - number: '30:6b '
        content: Hebrew <b>that covers the Testimony; </b>see note on 25:16.
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CEvery morning when Aaron maintains the lamps, he must burn
        fragrant incense on the altar. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And each evening when he lights the lamps, he must again burn incense
        in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s presence. This must be done from
        generation to generation. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Do not offer any unholy incense on this altar, or any burnt offerings,
        grain offerings, or liquid offerings.  '
      comments: []
    - title: Money for the Tabernacle
      content: "\u201COnce a year Aaron must purify[[COMMENT(0)]] the altar by smearing
        its horns with blood from the offering made to purify the people from their
        sin. This will be a regular, annual event from generation to generation,
        for this is the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s most holy altar.\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '30:10 '
        content: Or <b>make atonement for; </b>also in 30:10b.
    - title: 
      content: 'Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to Moses, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWhenever you take a census of the people of Israel, each man
        who is counted must pay a ransom for himself to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.
        Then no plague will strike the people as you count them. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Each person who is counted must give a small piece of silver as a
        sacred offering to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. (This payment is half
        a shekel,[[COMMENT(0)]] based on the sanctuary shekel, which equals twenty
        gerahs.) '
      comments:
      - number: '30:13 '
        content: Or <b>0.2 ounces </b>[6 grams].
    - title: 
      content: 'All who have reached their twentieth birthday must give this sacred
        offering to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When this offering is given to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> to
        purify your lives, making you right with him,[[COMMENT(0)]] the rich must
        not give more than the specified amount, and the poor must not give less. '
      comments:
      - number: '30:15 '
        content: Or <b>to make atonement for your lives; </b>similarly in 30:16.
    - title: Plans for the Washbasin
      content: "Receive this ransom money from the Israelites, and use it for the
        care of the Tabernacle.[[COMMENT(0)]] It will bring the Israelites to the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s attention, and it will purify your lives.\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '30:16 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Tent of Meeting; </b>also in 30:18, 20, 26, 36.
    - title: 
      content: 'Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to Moses, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CMake a bronze washbasin with a bronze stand. Place it between
        the Tabernacle and the altar, and fill it with water. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Aaron and his sons will wash their hands and feet there. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "They must wash with water whenever they go into the Tabernacle to
        appear before the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> and when they approach the
        altar to burn up their special gifts to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2014or
        they will die! "
      comments: []
    - title: The Anointing Oil
      content: "They must always wash their hands and feet, or they will die. This
        is a permanent law for Aaron and his descendants, to be observed from generation
        to generation.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to Moses, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CCollect choice spices\u201412-1/2 pounds of pure myrrh, 6-1/4
        pounds of fragrant cinnamon, 6-1/4 pounds of fragrant calamus,[[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '30:23 '
        content: Hebrew <b>500 [shekels] </b>[5.7 kilograms] <b>of pure myrrh, 250
          [shekels] </b>[2.9 kilograms] <b>of fragrant cinnamon, 250 [shekels] of
          fragrant calamus.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "and 12-1/2 pounds of cassia[[COMMENT(0)]]\u2014as measured by the
        weight of the sanctuary shekel. Also get one gallon of olive oil.[[COMMENT(1)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '30:24a '
        content: Hebrew <b>500 [shekels] </b>[5.7 kilograms] <b>of cassia.</b>
      - number: '30:24b '
        content: Hebrew <b>1 hin </b>[3.8 liters] <b>of olive oil.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'Like a skilled incense maker, blend these ingredients to make a holy
        anointing oil. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Use this sacred oil to anoint the Tabernacle, the Ark of the Covenant, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'the table and all its utensils, the lampstand and all its accessories,
        the incense altar, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'the altar of burnt offering and all its utensils, and the washbasin
        with its stand. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Consecrate them to make them absolutely holy. After this, whatever
        touches them will also become holy.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CAnoint Aaron and his sons also, consecrating them to serve
        me as priests. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And say to the people of Israel, \u2018This holy anointing oil is
        reserved for me from generation to generation. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'It must never be used to anoint anyone else, and you must never make
        any blend like it for yourselves. It is holy, and you must treat it as holy. '
      comments: []
    - title: The Incense
      content: "Anyone who makes a blend like it or anoints someone other than a
        priest will be cut off from the community.\u2019\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to Moses, \u201CGather
        fragrant spices\u2014resin droplets, mollusk shell, and galbanum\u2014and
        mix these fragrant spices with pure frankincense, weighed out in equal amounts. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Using the usual techniques of the incense maker, blend the spices
        together and sprinkle them with salt to produce a pure and holy incense. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Grind some of the mixture into a very fine powder and put it in front
        of the Ark of the Covenant,[[COMMENT(0)]] where I will meet with you in the
        Tabernacle. You must treat this incense as most holy. '
      comments:
      - number: '30:36 '
        content: Hebrew <b>in front of the Testimony; </b>see note on 25:16.
    - title: 
      content: 'Never use this formula to make this incense for yourselves. It is
        reserved for the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, and you must treat it as holy. '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: 'Craftsmen: Bezalel and Oholiab'
      content: '  Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to Moses, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CLook, I have specifically chosen Bezalel son of Uri, grandson
        of Hur, of the tribe of Judah. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I have filled him with the Spirit of God, giving him great wisdom,
        ability, and expertise in all kinds of crafts. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He is a master craftsman, expert in working with gold, silver, and
        bronze. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He is skilled in engraving and mounting gemstones and in carving
        wood. He is a master at every craft!  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CAnd I have personally appointed Oholiab son of Ahisamach, of
        the tribe of Dan, to be his assistant. Moreover, I have given special skill
        to all the gifted craftsmen so they can make all the things I have commanded
        you to make:  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "the Tabernacle;[[COMMENT(0)]]the Ark of the Covenant;[[COMMENT(1)]]the
        Ark\u2019s cover\u2014the place of atonement;all the furnishings of the Tabernacle;  "
      comments:
      - number: '31:7a '
        content: Hebrew <b>the Tent of Meeting.</b>
      - number: '31:7b '
        content: Hebrew <b>the Ark of the Testimony.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'the table and its utensils;the pure gold lampstand with all its accessories;the
        incense altar;  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'the altar of burnt offering with all its utensils;the washbasin with
        its stand;  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "the beautifully stitched garments\u2014the sacred garments for Aaron
        the priest, and the garments for his sons to wear as they minister as priests;  "
      comments: []
    - title: Instructions for the Sabbath
      content: "the anointing oil;the fragrant incense for the Holy Place.The craftsmen
        must make everything as I have commanded you.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> then gave these instructions to Moses: '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CTell the people of Israel: \u2018Be careful to keep my Sabbath
        day, for the Sabbath is a sign of the covenant between me and you from generation
        to generation. It is given so you may know that I am the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        who makes you holy. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'You must keep the Sabbath day, for it is a holy day for you. Anyone
        who desecrates it must be put to death; anyone who works on that day will
        be cut off from the community. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'You have six days each week for your ordinary work, but the seventh
        day must be a Sabbath day of complete rest, a holy day dedicated to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.
        Anyone who works on the Sabbath must be put to death. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The people of Israel must keep the Sabbath day by observing it from
        generation to generation. This is a covenant obligation for all time. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "It is a permanent sign of my covenant with the people of Israel.
        For in six days the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> made heaven and earth, but
        on the seventh day he stopped working and was refreshed.\u2019\u201D  "
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: The Gold Calf
      content: "  When the people saw how long it was taking Moses to come back down
        the mountain, they gathered around Aaron. \u201CCome on,\u201D they said,
        \u201Cmake us some gods who can lead us. We don\u2019t know what happened
        to this fellow Moses, who brought us here from the land of Egypt.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So Aaron said, \u201CTake the gold rings from the ears of your wives
        and sons and daughters, and bring them to me.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'All the people took the gold rings from their ears and brought them
        to Aaron. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Aaron took the gold, melted it down, and molded it into the
        shape of a calf. When the people saw it, they exclaimed, \u201CO Israel,
        these are the gods who brought you out of the land of Egypt!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Aaron saw how excited the people were, so he built an altar in front
        of the calf. Then he announced, \u201CTomorrow will be a festival to the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The people got up early the next morning to sacrifice burnt offerings
        and peace offerings. After this, they celebrated with feasting and drinking,
        and they indulged in pagan revelry.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> told Moses, \u201CQuick! Go down
        the mountain! Your people whom you brought from the land of Egypt have corrupted
        themselves. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "How quickly they have turned away from the way I commanded them to
        live! They have melted down gold and made a calf, and they have bowed down
        and sacrificed to it. They are saying, \u2018These are your gods, O Israel,
        who brought you out of the land of Egypt.\u2019\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said, \u201CI have seen how
        stubborn and rebellious these people are. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Now leave me alone so my fierce anger can blaze against them, and
        I will destroy them. Then I will make you, Moses, into a great nation.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But Moses tried to pacify the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> his God.
        \u201CO <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>!\u201D he said. \u201CWhy are you so
        angry with your own people whom you brought from the land of Egypt with such
        great power and such a strong hand? "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Why let the Egyptians say, \u2018Their God rescued them with the
        evil intention of slaughtering them in the mountains and wiping them from
        the face of the earth\u2019? Turn away from your fierce anger. Change your
        mind about this terrible disaster you have threatened against your people! "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Remember your servants Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob.[[COMMENT(0)]] You
        bound yourself with an oath to them, saying, \u2018I will make your descendants
        as numerous as the stars of heaven. And I will give them all of this land
        that I have promised to your descendants, and they will possess it forever.\u2019\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '32:13 '
        content: "Hebrew <b>Israel. </b>The names \u201CJacob\u201D and \u201CIsrael\u201D
          are often interchanged throughout the Old Testament, referring sometimes
          to the individual patriarch and sometimes to the nation."
    - title: 
      content: 'So the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> changed his mind about the terrible
        disaster he had threatened to bring on his people.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then Moses turned and went down the mountain. He held in his hands
        the two stone tablets inscribed with the terms of the covenant.[[COMMENT(0)]]
        They were inscribed on both sides, front and back. '
      comments:
      - number: '32:15 '
        content: Hebrew <b>the two tablets of the Testimony; </b>see note on 25:16.
    - title: 
      content: "These tablets were God\u2019s work; the words on them were written
        by God himself.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When Joshua heard the boisterous noise of the people shouting below
        them, he exclaimed to Moses, \u201CIt sounds like war in the camp!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But Moses replied, \u201CNo, it\u2019s not a shout of victory nor
        the wailing of defeat. I hear the sound of a celebration.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When they came near the camp, Moses saw the calf and the dancing,
        and he burned with anger. He threw the stone tablets to the ground, smashing
        them at the foot of the mountain. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He took the calf they had made and burned it. Then he ground it into
        powder, threw it into the water, and forced the people to drink it.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Finally, he turned to Aaron and demanded, \u201CWhat did these people
        do to you to make you bring such terrible sin upon them?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CDon\u2019t get so upset, my lord,\u201D Aaron replied. \u201CYou
        yourself know how evil these people are. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "They said to me, \u2018Make us gods who will lead us. We don\u2019t
        know what happened to this fellow Moses, who brought us here from the land
        of Egypt.\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So I told them, \u2018Whoever has gold jewelry, take it off.\u2019
        When they brought it to me, I simply threw it into the fire\u2014and out
        came this calf!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Moses saw that Aaron had let the people get completely out of control,
        much to the amusement of their enemies.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '32:25 '
        content: Or <b>out of control, and they mocked anyone who opposed them. </b>The
          meaning of the Hebrew is uncertain.
    - title: 
      content: "So he stood at the entrance to the camp and shouted, \u201CAll of
        you who are on the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s side, come here and
        join me.\u201D And all the Levites gathered around him.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Moses told them, \u201CThis is what the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        the God of Israel, says: Each of you, take your swords and go back and forth
        from one end of the camp to the other. Kill everyone\u2014even your brothers,
        friends, and neighbors.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The Levites obeyed Moses\u2019 command, and about 3,000 people died
        that day.  "
      comments: []
    - title: Moses Intercedes for Israel
      content: "Then Moses told the Levites, \u201CToday you have ordained yourselves[[COMMENT(0)]]
        for the service of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, for you obeyed him even
        though it meant killing your own sons and brothers. Today you have earned
        a blessing.\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '32:29 '
        content: As in Greek and Latin versions; Hebrew reads <b>Today ordain yourselves.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "The next day Moses said to the people, \u201CYou have committed a
        terrible sin, but I will go back up to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> on
        the mountain. Perhaps I will be able to obtain forgiveness[[COMMENT(0)]]
        for your sin.\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '32:30 '
        content: Or <b>to make atonement.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "So Moses returned to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> and said, \u201COh,
        what a terrible sin these people have committed. They have made gods of gold
        for themselves. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But now, if you will only forgive their sin\u2014but if not, erase
        my name from the record you have written!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> replied to Moses, \u201CNo, I
        will erase the name of everyone who has sinned against me. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Now go, lead the people to the place I told you about. Look! My angel
        will lead the way before you. And when I come to call the people to account,
        I will certainly hold them responsible for their sins.\u201D  "
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: 
      content: "  The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to Moses, \u201CGet going,
        you and the people you brought up from the land of Egypt. Go up to the land
        I swore to give to Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob. I told them, \u2018I will give
        this land to your descendants.\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And I will send an angel before you to drive out the Canaanites,
        Amorites, Hittites, Perizzites, Hivites, and Jebusites. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Go up to this land that flows with milk and honey. But I will not
        travel among you, for you are a stubborn and rebellious people. If I did,
        I would surely destroy you along the way.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When the people heard these stern words, they went into mourning
        and stopped wearing their jewelry and fine clothes. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "For the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had told Moses to tell them,
        \u201CYou are a stubborn and rebellious people. If I were to travel with
        you for even a moment, I would destroy you. Remove your jewelry and fine
        clothes while I decide what to do with you.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So from the time they left Mount Sinai,[[COMMENT(0)]] the Israelites
        wore no more jewelry or fine clothes.  '
      comments:
      - number: '33:6 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Horeb, </b>another name for Sinai.
    - title: 
      content: "It was Moses\u2019 practice to take the Tent of Meeting[[COMMENT(0)]]
        and set it up some distance from the camp. Everyone who wanted to make a
        request of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> would go to the Tent of Meeting
        outside the camp.  "
      comments:
      - number: '33:7 '
        content: "This \u201CTent of Meeting\u201D is different from the Tabernacle
          described in chapters 26 and 36."
    - title: 
      content: 'Whenever Moses went out to the Tent of Meeting, all the people would
        get up and stand in the entrances of their own tents. They would all watch
        Moses until he disappeared inside. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'As he went into the tent, the pillar of cloud would come down and
        hover at its entrance while the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> spoke with Moses. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When the people saw the cloud standing at the entrance of the tent,
        they would stand and bow down in front of their own tents. '
      comments: []
    - title: "Moses Sees the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s Glory"
      content: 'Inside the Tent of Meeting, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> would
        speak to Moses face to face, as one speaks to a friend. Afterward Moses would
        return to the camp, but the young man who assisted him, Joshua son of Nun,
        would remain behind in the Tent of Meeting.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "One day Moses said to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, \u201CYou
        have been telling me, \u2018Take these people up to the Promised Land.\u2019
        But you haven\u2019t told me whom you will send with me. You have told me,
        \u2018I know you by name, and I look favorably on you.\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "If it is true that you look favorably on me, let me know your ways
        so I may understand you more fully and continue to enjoy your favor. And
        remember that this nation is your very own people.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> replied, \u201CI will personally
        go with you, Moses, and I will give you rest\u2014everything will be fine
        for you.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Moses said, \u201CIf you don\u2019t personally go with us, don\u2019t
        make us leave this place. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "How will anyone know that you look favorably on me\u2014on me and
        on your people\u2014if you don\u2019t go with us? For your presence among
        us sets your people and me apart from all other people on the earth.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> replied to Moses, \u201CI will indeed
        do what you have asked, for I look favorably on you, and I know you by name.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Moses responded, \u201CThen show me your glorious presence.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> replied, \u201CI will make all my
        goodness pass before you, and I will call out my name, Yahweh,[[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>
        before you. For I will show mercy to anyone I choose, and I will show compassion
        to anyone I choose. </smallcaps>"
      comments:
      - number: '33:19 '
        content: "<b>Yahweh </b>is a transliteration of the proper name <b>YHWH </b>that
          is sometimes rendered \u201CJehovah\u201D; in this translation it is usually
          rendered \u201Cthe <span class=\"ChapterContent_nd__ECPAf\">Lord</span>\u201D
          (note the use of small capitals)."
    - title: 
      content: "But you may not look directly at my face, for no one may see me and
        live.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> continued, \u201CLook, stand near
        me on this rock. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'As my glorious presence passes by, I will hide you in the crevice
        of the rock and cover you with my hand until I have passed by. '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: A New Copy of the Covenant
      content: "  Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> told Moses, \u201CChisel out
        two stone tablets like the first ones. I will write on them the same words
        that were on the tablets you smashed. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Be ready in the morning to climb up Mount Sinai and present yourself
        to me on the top of the mountain. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "No one else may come with you. In fact, no one is to appear anywhere
        on the mountain. Do not even let the flocks or herds graze near the mountain.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So Moses chiseled out two tablets of stone like the first ones. Early
        in the morning he climbed Mount Sinai as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        had commanded him, and he carried the two stone tablets in his hands.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> came down in a cloud and stood
        there with him; and he called out his own name, Yahweh.[[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps> 
        </smallcaps>
      comments:
      - number: '34:5 '
        content: "<b>Yahweh </b>is a transliteration of the proper name <b>YHWH </b>that
          is sometimes rendered \u201CJehovah\u201D; in this translation it is usually
          rendered \u201Cthe <span class=\"ChapterContent_nd__ECPAf\">Lord</span>\u201D
          (note the use of small capitals)."
    - title: 
      content: "The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> passed in front of Moses, calling
        out,\u201CYahweh![[COMMENT(0)]] The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>!The God of
        compassion and mercy!I am slow to angerand filled with unfailing love and
        faithfulness.  "
      comments:
      - number: '34:6 '
        content: See note on 34:5.
    - title: 
      content: "I lavish unfailing love to a thousand generations.[[COMMENT(0)]]I
        forgive iniquity, rebellion, and sin.But I do not excuse the guilty.I lay
        the sins of the parents upon their children and grandchildren;the entire
        family is affected\u2014even children in the third and fourth generations.\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '34:7 '
        content: Hebrew <b>for thousands.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'Moses immediately threw himself to the ground and worshiped. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And he said, \u201CO Lord, if it is true that I have found favor
        with you, then please travel with us. Yes, this is a stubborn and rebellious
        people, but please forgive our iniquity and our sins. Claim us as your own
        special possession.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> replied, \u201CListen, I am making
        a covenant with you in the presence of all your people. I will perform miracles
        that have never been performed anywhere in all the earth or in any nation.
        And all the people around you will see the power of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2014the
        awesome power I will display for you. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But listen carefully to everything I command you today. Then I will
        go ahead of you and drive out the Amorites, Canaanites, Hittites, Perizzites,
        Hivites, and Jebusites.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CBe very careful never to make a treaty with the people who
        live in the land where you are going. If you do, you will follow their evil
        ways and be trapped. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Instead, you must break down their pagan altars, smash their sacred
        pillars, and cut down their Asherah poles. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'You must worship no other gods, for the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        whose very name is Jealous, is a God who is jealous about his relationship
        with you.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CYou must not make a treaty of any kind with the people living
        in the land. They lust after their gods, offering sacrifices to them. They
        will invite you to join them in their sacrificial meals, and you will go
        with them. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then you will accept their daughters, who sacrifice to other gods,
        as wives for your sons. And they will seduce your sons to commit adultery
        against me by worshiping other gods. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'You must not make any gods of molten metal for yourselves.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CYou must celebrate the Festival of Unleavened Bread. For seven
        days the bread you eat must be made without yeast, just as I commanded you.
        Celebrate this festival annually at the appointed time in early spring, in
        the month of Abib,[[COMMENT(0)]] for that is the anniversary of your departure
        from Egypt.  "
      comments:
      - number: '34:18 '
        content: Hebrew <b>appointed time in the month of Abib. </b>This first month
          of the ancient Hebrew lunar calendar usually occurs within the months of
          March and April.
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThe firstborn of every animal belongs to me, including the
        firstborn males[[COMMENT(0)]] from your herds of cattle and your flocks of
        sheep and goats. "
      comments:
      - number: '34:19 '
        content: As in Greek version; the meaning of the Hebrew word is uncertain.
    - title: 
      content: "A firstborn donkey may be bought back from the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        by presenting a lamb or young goat in its place. But if you do not buy it
        back, you must break its neck. However, you must buy back every firstborn
        son.\u201CNo one may appear before me without an offering.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CYou have six days each week for your ordinary work, but on
        the seventh day you must stop working, even during the seasons of plowing
        and harvest.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CYou must celebrate the Festival of Harvest[[COMMENT(0)]] with
        the first crop of the wheat harvest, and celebrate the Festival of the Final
        Harvest[[COMMENT(1)]] at the end of the harvest season. "
      comments:
      - number: '34:22a '
        content: Hebrew <b>Festival of Weeks; </b>compare 23:16. This was later called
          the Festival of Pentecost. It is celebrated today as Shavuot (or Shabuoth).
      - number: '34:22b '
        content: Or <b>Festival of Ingathering. </b>This was later called the Festival
          of Shelters or Festival of Tabernacles (see Lev 23:33-36). It is celebrated
          today as Sukkot (or Succoth).
    - title: 
      content: 'Three times each year every man in Israel must appear before the
        Sovereign, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the God of Israel. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I will drive out the other nations ahead of you and expand your territory,
        so no one will covet and conquer your land while you appear before the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        your God three times each year.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CYou must not offer the blood of my sacrificial offerings together
        with any baked goods containing yeast. And none of the meat of the Passover
        sacrifice may be kept over until the next morning.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CAs you harvest your crops, bring the very best of the first
        harvest to the house of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> your God.\u201CYou
        must not cook a young goat in its mother\u2019s milk.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to Moses, \u201CWrite down
        all these instructions, for they represent the terms of the covenant I am
        making with you and with Israel.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Moses remained there on the mountain with the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        forty days and forty nights. In all that time he ate no bread and drank no
        water. And the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>[[COMMENT(0)]] wrote the terms
        of the covenant\u2014the Ten Commandments[[COMMENT(1)]]\u2014on the stone
        tablets.  "
      comments:
      - number: '34:28a '
        content: Hebrew <b>he.</b>
      - number: '34:28b '
        content: Hebrew <b>the ten words.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "When Moses came down Mount Sinai carrying the two stone tablets inscribed
        with the terms of the covenant,[[COMMENT(0)]] he wasn\u2019t aware that his
        face had become radiant because he had spoken to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. "
      comments:
      - number: '34:29 '
        content: Hebrew <b>the two tablets of the Testimony; </b>see note on 25:16.
    - title: 
      content: "So when Aaron and the people of Israel saw the radiance of Moses\u2019
        face, they were afraid to come near him.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But Moses called out to them and asked Aaron and all the leaders
        of the community to come over, and he talked with them. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then all the people of Israel approached him, and Moses gave them
        all the instructions the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had given him on Mount
        Sinai. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When Moses finished speaking with them, he covered his face with
        a veil. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But whenever he went into the Tent of Meeting to speak with the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        he would remove the veil until he came out again. Then he would give the
        people whatever instructions the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had given him, '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Instructions for the Sabbath
      content: "  Then Moses called together the whole community of Israel and told
        them, \u201CThese are the instructions the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> has
        commanded you to follow. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'You have six days each week for your ordinary work, but the seventh
        day must be a Sabbath day of complete rest, a holy day dedicated to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.
        Anyone who works on that day must be put to death. '
      comments: []
    - title: Offerings for the Tabernacle
      content: "You must not even light a fire in any of your homes on the Sabbath.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Moses said to the whole community of Israel, \u201CThis is what
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> has commanded: "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Take a sacred offering for the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. Let those
        with generous hearts present the following gifts to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>:gold,
        silver, and bronze;  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'blue, purple, and scarlet thread;fine linen and goat hair for cloth;  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'tanned ram skins and fine goatskin leather;acacia wood;  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'olive oil for the lamps;spices for the anointing oil and the fragrant
        incense;  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "onyx stones, and other gemstones to be set in the ephod and the priest\u2019s
        chestpiece.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CCome, all of you who are gifted craftsmen. Construct everything
        that the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> has commanded:  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'the Tabernacle and its sacred tent, its covering, clasps, frames,
        crossbars, posts, and bases;  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "the Ark and its carrying poles;the Ark\u2019s cover\u2014the place
        of atonement;the inner curtain to shield the Ark;  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'the table, its carrying poles, and all its utensils;the Bread of
        the Presence;  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'for light, the lampstand, its accessories, the lamp cups, and the
        olive oil for lighting;  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'the incense altar and its carrying poles;the anointing oil and fragrant
        incense;the curtain for the entrance of the Tabernacle;  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'the altar of burnt offering;the bronze grating of the altar and its
        carrying poles and utensils;the washbasin with its stand;  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'the curtains for the walls of the courtyard;the posts and their bases;the
        curtain for the entrance to the courtyard;  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'the tent pegs of the Tabernacle and courtyard and their ropes;  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "the beautifully stitched garments for the priests to wear while ministering
        in the Holy Place\u2014the sacred garments for Aaron the priest, and the
        garments for his sons to wear as they minister as priests.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So the whole community of Israel left Moses and returned to their
        tents. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'All whose hearts were stirred and whose spirits were moved came and
        brought their sacred offerings to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. They brought
        all the materials needed for the Tabernacle,[[COMMENT(0)]] for the performance
        of its rituals, and for the sacred garments. '
      comments:
      - number: '35:21 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Tent of Meeting.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "Both men and women came, all whose hearts were willing. They brought
        to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> their offerings of gold\u2014brooches,
        earrings, rings from their fingers, and necklaces. They presented gold objects
        of every kind as a special offering to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'All those who owned the following items willingly brought them: blue,
        purple, and scarlet thread; fine linen and goat hair for cloth; and tanned
        ram skins and fine goatskin leather. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And all who had silver and bronze objects gave them as a sacred offering
        to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. And those who had acacia wood brought
        it for use in the project.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'All the women who were skilled in sewing and spinning prepared blue,
        purple, and scarlet thread, and fine linen cloth. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'All the women who were willing used their skills to spin the goat
        hair into yarn. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The leaders brought onyx stones and the special gemstones to be set
        in the ephod and the priest\u2019s chestpiece. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They also brought spices and olive oil for the light, the anointing
        oil, and the fragrant incense. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So the people of Israel\u2014every man and woman who was eager to
        help in the work the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had given them through Moses\u2014brought
        their gifts and gave them freely to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Moses told the people of Israel, \u201CThe <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        has specifically chosen Bezalel son of Uri, grandson of Hur, of the tribe
        of Judah. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> has filled Bezalel with the Spirit
        of God, giving him great wisdom, ability, and expertise in all kinds of crafts. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He is a master craftsman, expert in working with gold, silver, and
        bronze. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He is skilled in engraving and mounting gemstones and in carving
        wood. He is a master at every craft. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> has given both him and Oholiab
        son of Ahisamach, of the tribe of Dan, the ability to teach their skills
        to others. '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: 
      content: "  \u201CThe <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> has gifted Bezalel, Oholiab,
        and the other skilled craftsmen with wisdom and ability to perform any task
        involved in building the sanctuary. Let them construct and furnish the Tabernacle,
        just as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> has commanded.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So Moses summoned Bezalel and Oholiab and all the others who were
        specially gifted by the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> and were eager to get
        to work. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Moses gave them the materials donated by the people of Israel as
        sacred offerings for the completion of the sanctuary. But the people continued
        to bring additional gifts each morning. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Finally the craftsmen who were working on the sanctuary left their
        work. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "They went to Moses and reported, \u201CThe people have given more
        than enough materials to complete the job the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        has commanded us to do!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So Moses gave the command, and this message was sent throughout the
        camp: \u201CMen and women, don\u2019t prepare any more gifts for the sanctuary.
        We have enough!\u201D So the people stopped bringing their sacred offerings. "
      comments: []
    - title: Building the Tabernacle
      content: 'Their contributions were more than enough to complete the whole project.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The skilled craftsmen made ten curtains of finely woven linen for
        the Tabernacle. Then Bezalel[[COMMENT(0)]] decorated the curtains with blue,
        purple, and scarlet thread and with skillfully embroidered cherubim. '
      comments:
      - number: '36:8 '
        content: Hebrew <b>he; </b>also in 36:16, 20, 35. See 37:1.
    - title: 
      content: "All ten curtains were exactly the same size\u201442 feet long and
        6 feet wide.[[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '36:9 '
        content: Hebrew <b>28 cubits </b>[12.9 meters] <b>long and 4 cubits </b>[1.8
          meters] <b>wide.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'Five of these curtains were joined together to make one long curtain,
        and the other five were joined to make a second long curtain. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He made fifty loops of blue yarn and put them along the edge of the
        last curtain in each set. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The fifty loops along the edge of one curtain matched the fifty loops
        along the edge of the other curtain. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then he made fifty gold clasps and fastened the long curtains together
        with the clasps. In this way, the Tabernacle was made of one continuous piece.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He made eleven curtains of goat-hair cloth to serve as a tent covering
        for the Tabernacle. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "These eleven curtains were all exactly the same size\u201445 feet
        long and 6 feet wide.[[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '36:15 '
        content: Hebrew <b>30 cubits </b>[13.8 meters] <b>long and 4 cubits </b>[1.8
          meters] <b>wide.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'Bezalel joined five of these curtains together to make one long curtain,
        and the other six were joined to make a second long curtain. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He made fifty loops for the edge of each large curtain. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He also made fifty bronze clasps to fasten the long curtains together.
        In this way, the tent covering was made of one continuous piece. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He completed the tent covering with a layer of tanned ram skins and
        a layer of fine goatskin leather.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'For the framework of the Tabernacle, Bezalel constructed frames of
        acacia wood. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Each frame was 15 feet high and 27 inches wide,[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '36:21 '
        content: Hebrew <b>10 cubits </b>[4.6 meters] <b>high and 1.5 cubits </b>[69
          centimeters] <b>wide.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'with two pegs under each frame. All the frames were identical. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He made twenty of these frames to support the curtains on the south
        side of the Tabernacle. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He also made forty silver bases\u2014two bases under each frame,
        with the pegs fitting securely into the bases. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'For the north side of the Tabernacle, he made another twenty frames, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'with their forty silver bases, two bases under each frame. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He made six frames for the rear\u2014the west side of the Tabernacle\u2014 "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'along with two additional frames to reinforce the rear corners of
        the Tabernacle. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'These corner frames were matched at the bottom and firmly attached
        at the top with a single ring, forming a single corner unit. Both of these
        corner units were made the same way. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So there were eight frames at the rear of the Tabernacle, set in
        sixteen silver bases\u2014two bases under each frame.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then he made crossbars of acacia wood to link the frames, five crossbars
        for the north side of the Tabernacle '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'and five for the south side. He also made five crossbars for the
        rear of the Tabernacle, which faced west. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He made the middle crossbar to attach halfway up the frames; it ran
        all the way from one end of the Tabernacle to the other. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He overlaid the frames with gold and made gold rings to hold the
        crossbars. Then he overlaid the crossbars with gold as well.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'For the inside of the Tabernacle, Bezalel made a special curtain
        of finely woven linen. He decorated it with blue, purple, and scarlet thread
        and with skillfully embroidered cherubim. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'For the curtain, he made four posts of acacia wood and four gold
        hooks. He overlaid the posts with gold and set them in four silver bases.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then he made another curtain for the entrance to the sacred tent.
        He made it of finely woven linen and embroidered it with exquisite designs
        using blue, purple, and scarlet thread. '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Building the Ark of the Covenant
      content: "  Next Bezalel made the Ark of acacia wood\u2014a sacred chest 45
        inches long, 27 inches wide, and 27 inches high.[[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '37:1 '
        content: Hebrew <b>2.5 cubits </b>[115 centimeters] <b>long, 1.5 cubits </b>[69
          centimeters] <b>wide, and 1.5 cubits high.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'He overlaid it inside and outside with pure gold, and he ran a molding
        of gold all around it. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He cast four gold rings and attached them to its four feet, two rings
        on each side. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then he made poles from acacia wood and overlaid them with gold. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He inserted the poles into the rings at the sides of the Ark to carry
        it.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then he made the Ark\u2019s cover\u2014the place of atonement\u2014from
        pure gold. It was 45 inches long and 27 inches wide.[[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '37:6 '
        content: Hebrew <b>2.5 cubits </b>[115 centimeters] <b>long and 1.5 cubits
          </b>[69 centimeters] <b>wide.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'He made two cherubim from hammered gold and placed them on the two
        ends of the atonement cover. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He molded the cherubim on each end of the atonement cover, making
        it all of one piece of gold. '
      comments: []
    - title: Building the Table
      content: 'The cherubim faced each other and looked down on the atonement cover.
        With their wings spread above it, they protected it.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then Bezalel[[COMMENT(0)]] made the table of acacia wood, 36 inches
        long, 18 inches wide, and 27 inches high.[[COMMENT(1)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '37:10a '
        content: Hebrew <b>he; </b>also in 37:17, 25.
      - number: '37:10b '
        content: Hebrew <b>2 cubits </b>[92 centimeters] <b>long, 1 cubit </b>[46
          centimeters] <b>wide, and 1.5 cubits </b>[69 centimeters] <b>high.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'He overlaid it with pure gold and ran a gold molding around the edge. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He decorated it with a 3-inch border[[COMMENT(0)]] all around, and
        he ran a gold molding along the border. '
      comments:
      - number: '37:12 '
        content: Hebrew <b>a border of a handbreadth </b>[8 centimeters].
    - title: 
      content: 'Then he cast four gold rings for the table and attached them at the
        four corners next to the four legs. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The rings were attached near the border to hold the poles that were
        used to carry the table. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He made these poles from acacia wood and overlaid them with gold. '
      comments: []
    - title: Building the Lampstand
      content: "Then he made special containers of pure gold for the table\u2014bowls,
        ladles, jars, and pitchers\u2014to be used in pouring out liquid offerings.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Bezalel made the lampstand of pure, hammered gold. He made the
        entire lampstand and its decorations of one piece\u2014the base, center stem,
        lamp cups, buds, and petals. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The lampstand had six branches going out from the center stem, three
        on each side. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Each of the six branches had three lamp cups shaped like almond blossoms,
        complete with buds and petals. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The center stem of the lampstand was crafted with four lamp cups
        shaped like almond blossoms, complete with buds and petals. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'There was an almond bud beneath each pair of branches where the six
        branches extended from the center stem, all made of one piece. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The almond buds and branches were all of one piece with the center
        stem, and they were hammered from pure gold.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He also made seven lamps for the lampstand, lamp snuffers, and trays,
        all of pure gold. '
      comments: []
    - title: Building the Incense Altar
      content: 'The entire lampstand, along with its accessories, was made from 75
        pounds[[COMMENT(0)]] of pure gold.  '
      comments:
      - number: '37:24 '
        content: Hebrew <b>1 talent </b>[34 kilograms].
    - title: 
      content: 'Then Bezalel made the incense altar of acacia wood. It was 18 inches
        square and 36 inches high,[[COMMENT(0)]] with horns at the corners carved
        from the same piece of wood as the altar itself. '
      comments:
      - number: '37:25 '
        content: Hebrew <b>1 cubit </b>[46 centimeters] <b>long and 1 cubit wide,
          a square, and 2 cubits </b>[92 centimeters] <b>high.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'He overlaid the top, sides, and horns of the altar with pure gold,
        and he ran a gold molding around the entire altar. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He made two gold rings and attached them on opposite sides of the
        altar below the gold molding to hold the carrying poles. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He made the poles of acacia wood and overlaid them with gold.  '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Building the Altar of Burnt Offering
      content: '  Next Bezalel[[COMMENT(0)]] used acacia wood to construct the square
        altar of burnt offering. It was 7-1/2 feet wide, 7-1/2 feet long, and 4-1/2
        feet high.[[COMMENT(1)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '38:1a '
        content: Hebrew <b>he; </b>also in 38:8, 9.
      - number: '38:1b '
        content: Hebrew <b>5 cubits </b>[2.3 meters] <b>wide, 5 cubits long, a square,
          and 3 cubits </b>[1.4 meters] <b>high.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'He made horns for each of its four corners so that the horns and
        altar were all one piece. He overlaid the altar with bronze. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then he made all the altar utensils of bronze\u2014the ash buckets,
        shovels, basins, meat forks, and firepans. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Next he made a bronze grating and installed it halfway down the side
        of the altar, under the ledge. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He cast four rings and attached them to the corners of the bronze
        grating to hold the carrying poles. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He made the poles from acacia wood and overlaid them with bronze. '
      comments: []
    - title: Building the Washbasin
      content: 'He inserted the poles through the rings on the sides of the altar.
        The altar was hollow and was made from planks.  '
      comments: []
    - title: Building the Courtyard
      content: 'Bezalel made the bronze washbasin and its bronze stand from bronze
        mirrors donated by the women who served at the entrance of the Tabernacle.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '38:8 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Tent of Meeting; </b>also in 38:30.
    - title: 
      content: 'Then Bezalel made the courtyard, which was enclosed with curtains
        made of finely woven linen. On the south side the curtains were 150 feet
        long.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '38:9 '
        content: Hebrew <b>100 cubits </b>[46 meters]; also in 38:11.
    - title: 
      content: 'They were held up by twenty posts set securely in twenty bronze bases.
        He hung the curtains with silver hooks and rings. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He made a similar set of curtains for the north side\u2014150 feet
        of curtains held up by twenty posts set securely in bronze bases. He hung
        the curtains with silver hooks and rings. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The curtains on the west end of the courtyard were 75 feet long,[[COMMENT(0)]]
        hung with silver hooks and rings and supported by ten posts set into ten
        bases. '
      comments:
      - number: '38:12 '
        content: Hebrew <b>50 cubits </b>[23 meters]; also in 38:13.
    - title: 
      content: 'The east end, the front, was also 75 feet long.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The courtyard entrance was on the east end, flanked by two curtains.
        The curtain on the right side was 22-1/2 feet long[[COMMENT(0)]] and was
        supported by three posts set into three bases. '
      comments:
      - number: '38:14 '
        content: Hebrew <b>15 cubits </b>[6.9 meters]; also in 38:15.
    - title: 
      content: 'The curtain on the left side was also 22-1/2 feet long and was supported
        by three posts set into three bases. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'All the curtains used in the courtyard were made of finely woven
        linen. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Each post had a bronze base, and all the hooks and rings were silver.
        The tops of the posts of the courtyard were overlaid with silver, and the
        rings to hold up the curtains were made of silver.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He made the curtain for the entrance to the courtyard of finely woven
        linen, and he decorated it with beautiful embroidery in blue, purple, and
        scarlet thread. It was 30 feet long, and its height was 7-1/2 feet,[[COMMENT(0)]]
        just like the curtains of the courtyard walls. '
      comments:
      - number: '38:18 '
        content: Hebrew <b>20 cubits </b>[9.2 meters] <b>long and 5 cubits </b>[2.3
          meters] <b>high.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'It was supported by four posts, each set securely in its own bronze
        base. The tops of the posts were overlaid with silver, and the hooks and
        rings were also made of silver.  '
      comments: []
    - title: Inventory of Materials
      content: 'All the tent pegs used in the Tabernacle and courtyard were made
        of bronze.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'This is an inventory of the materials used in building the Tabernacle
        of the Covenant.[[COMMENT(0)]] The Levites compiled the figures, as Moses
        directed, and Ithamar son of Aaron the priest served as recorder. '
      comments:
      - number: '38:21 '
        content: Hebrew <b>the Tabernacle, the Tabernacle of the Testimony.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'Bezalel son of Uri, grandson of Hur, of the tribe of Judah, made
        everything just as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had commanded Moses. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He was assisted by Oholiab son of Ahisamach, of the tribe of Dan,
        a craftsman expert at engraving, designing, and embroidering with blue, purple,
        and scarlet thread on fine linen cloth.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The people brought special offerings of gold totaling 2,193 pounds,[[COMMENT(0)]]
        as measured by the weight of the sanctuary shekel. This gold was used throughout
        the Tabernacle.  '
      comments:
      - number: '38:24 '
        content: Hebrew <b>29 talents and 730 shekels </b>[994 kilograms]. Each shekel
          weighed about 0.4 ounces or 11 grams.
    - title: 
      content: 'The whole community of Israel gave 7,545 pounds[[COMMENT(0)]] of
        silver, as measured by the weight of the sanctuary shekel. '
      comments:
      - number: '38:25 '
        content: Hebrew <b>100 talents and 1,775 shekels </b>[3,420 kilograms].
    - title: 
      content: 'This silver came from the tax collected from each man registered
        in the census. (The tax is one beka, which is half a shekel,[[COMMENT(0)]]
        based on the sanctuary shekel.) The tax was collected from 603,550 men who
        had reached their twentieth birthday. '
      comments:
      - number: '38:26 '
        content: Or <b>0.2 ounces </b>[6 grams].
    - title: 
      content: 'The hundred bases for the frames of the sanctuary walls and for the
        posts supporting the inner curtain required 7,500 pounds of silver, about
        75 pounds for each base.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '38:27 '
        content: Hebrew <b>100 talents </b>[3,400 kilograms] <b>of silver, 1 talent
          </b>[34 kilograms] <b>for each base.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'The remaining 45 pounds[[COMMENT(0)]] of silver was used to make
        the hooks and rings and to overlay the tops of the posts.  '
      comments:
      - number: '38:28 '
        content: Hebrew <b>1,775 [shekels] </b>[20.2 kilograms].
    - title: 
      content: 'The people also brought as special offerings 5,310 pounds[[COMMENT(0)]]
        of bronze, '
      comments:
      - number: '38:29 '
        content: Hebrew <b>70 talents and 2,400 shekels </b>[2,407 kilograms].
    - title: 
      content: 'which was used for casting the bases for the posts at the entrance
        to the Tabernacle, and for the bronze altar with its bronze grating and all
        the altar utensils. '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Clothing for the PriestsMaking the Ephod
      content: "  The craftsmen made beautiful sacred garments of blue, purple, and
        scarlet cloth\u2014clothing for Aaron to wear while ministering in the Holy
        Place, just as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had commanded Moses.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Bezalel[[COMMENT(0)]] made the ephod of finely woven linen and embroidered
        it with gold and with blue, purple, and scarlet thread. '
      comments:
      - number: '39:2 '
        content: Hebrew <b>He; </b>also in 39:8, 22.
    - title: 
      content: 'He made gold thread by hammering out thin sheets of gold and cutting
        it into fine strands. With great skill and care, he worked it into the fine
        linen with the blue, purple, and scarlet thread.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The ephod consisted of two pieces, front and back, joined at the
        shoulders with two shoulder-pieces. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The decorative sash was made of the same materials: finely woven
        linen embroidered with gold and with blue, purple, and scarlet thread, just
        as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had commanded Moses. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They mounted the two onyx stones in settings of gold filigree. The
        stones were engraved with the names of the tribes of Israel, just as a seal
        is engraved. '
      comments: []
    - title: Making the Chestpiece
      content: 'He fastened these stones on the shoulder-pieces of the ephod as a
        reminder that the priest represents the people of Israel. All this was done
        just as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had commanded Moses.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Bezalel made the chestpiece with great skill and care. He made it
        to match the ephod, using finely woven linen embroidered with gold and with
        blue, purple, and scarlet thread. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He made the chestpiece of a single piece of cloth folded to form
        a pouch nine inches[[COMMENT(0)]] square. '
      comments:
      - number: '39:9 '
        content: Hebrew <b>1 span </b>[23 centimeters].
    - title: 
      content: 'They mounted four rows of gemstones[[COMMENT(0)]] on it. The first
        row contained a red carnelian, a pale-green peridot, and an emerald. '
      comments:
      - number: '39:10 '
        content: The identification of some of these gemstones is uncertain.
    - title: 
      content: 'The second row contained a turquoise, a blue lapis lazuli, and a
        white moonstone. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The third row contained an orange jacinth, an agate, and a purple
        amethyst. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The fourth row contained a blue-green beryl, an onyx, and a green
        jasper. All these stones were set in gold filigree. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Each stone represented one of the twelve sons of Israel, and the
        name of that tribe was engraved on it like a seal.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'To attach the chestpiece to the ephod, they made braided cords of
        pure gold thread. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They also made two settings of gold filigree and two gold rings and
        attached them to the top corners of the chestpiece. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They tied the two gold cords to the rings on the chestpiece. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They tied the other ends of the cords to the gold settings on the
        shoulder-pieces of the ephod. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then they made two more gold rings and attached them to the inside
        edges of the chestpiece next to the ephod. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then they made two more gold rings and attached them to the front
        of the ephod, below the shoulder-pieces, just above the knot where the decorative
        sash was fastened to the ephod. '
      comments: []
    - title: Additional Clothing for the Priests
      content: 'They attached the bottom rings of the chestpiece to the rings on
        the ephod with blue cords. In this way, the chestpiece was held securely
        to the ephod above the decorative sash. All this was done just as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        had commanded Moses.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Bezalel made the robe that is worn with the ephod from a single piece
        of blue woven cloth, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "with an opening for Aaron\u2019s head in the middle of it. The opening
        was reinforced with a woven collar[[COMMENT(0)]] so it would not tear. "
      comments:
      - number: '39:23 '
        content: The meaning of the Hebrew is uncertain.
    - title: 
      content: 'They made pomegranates of blue, purple, and scarlet yarn, and attached
        them to the hem of the robe. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They also made bells of pure gold and placed them between the pomegranates
        along the hem of the robe, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'with bells and pomegranates alternating all around the hem. This
        robe was to be worn whenever the priest ministered before the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        just as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had commanded Moses.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They made tunics for Aaron and his sons from fine linen cloth. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The turban and the special head coverings were made of fine linen,
        and the undergarments were also made of finely woven linen. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The sashes were made of finely woven linen and embroidered with blue,
        purple, and scarlet thread, just as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had commanded
        Moses.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Finally, they made the sacred medallion\u2014the badge of holiness\u2014of
        pure gold. They engraved it like a seal with these words: <smallcaps>Holy
        to the Lord</smallcaps>. "
      comments: []
    - title: Moses Inspects the Work
      content: "They attached the medallion with a blue cord to Aaron\u2019s turban,
        just as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had commanded Moses.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And so at last the Tabernacle[[COMMENT(0)]] was finished. The Israelites
        had done everything just as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had commanded
        Moses. '
      comments:
      - number: '39:32 '
        content: Hebrew <b>the Tabernacle, the Tent of Meeting; </b>also in 39:40.
    - title: 
      content: 'And they brought the entire Tabernacle to Moses:the sacred tent with
        all its furnishings, clasps, frames, crossbars, posts, and bases;  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'the tent coverings of tanned ram skins and fine goatskin leather;the
        inner curtain to shield the Ark;  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "the Ark of the Covenant[[COMMENT(0)]] and its carrying poles;the
        Ark\u2019s cover\u2014the place of atonement;  "
      comments:
      - number: '39:35 '
        content: Or <b>Ark of the Testimony.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'the table and all its utensils;the Bread of the Presence;  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'the pure gold lampstand with its symmetrical lamp cups, all its accessories,
        and the olive oil for lighting;  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'the gold altar;the anointing oil and fragrant incense;the curtain
        for the entrance of the sacred tent;  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'the bronze altar;the bronze grating and its carrying poles and utensils;the
        washbasin with its stand;  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'the curtains for the walls of the courtyard;the posts and their bases;the
        curtain for the entrance to the courtyard;the ropes and tent pegs;all the
        furnishings to be used in worship at the Tabernacle;  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "the beautifully stitched garments for the priests to wear while ministering
        in the Holy Place\u2014the sacred garments for Aaron the priest, and the
        garments for his sons to wear as they minister as priests.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So the people of Israel followed all of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        instructions to Moses. "
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: The Tabernacle Completed
      content: '  Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to Moses, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CSet up the Tabernacle[[COMMENT(0)]] on the first day of the
        new year.[[COMMENT(1)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '40:2a '
        content: Hebrew <b>the Tabernacle, the Tent of Meeting; </b>also in 40:6,
          29.
      - number: '40:2b '
        content: Hebrew <b>the first day of the first month. </b>This day of the
          ancient Hebrew lunar calendar occurred in March or April.
    - title: 
      content: 'Place the Ark of the Covenant[[COMMENT(0)]] inside, and install the
        inner curtain to enclose the Ark within the Most Holy Place. '
      comments:
      - number: '40:3 '
        content: Or <b>Ark of the Testimony; </b>also in 40:5, 21.
    - title: 
      content: 'Then bring in the table, and arrange the utensils on it. And bring
        in the lampstand, and set up the lamps.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CPlace the gold incense altar in front of the Ark of the Covenant.
        Then hang the curtain at the entrance of the Tabernacle. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Place the altar of burnt offering in front of the Tabernacle entrance. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Set the washbasin between the Tabernacle[[COMMENT(0)]] and the altar,
        and fill it with water. '
      comments:
      - number: '40:7 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Tent of Meeting; </b>also in 40:12, 22, 24, 26, 30, 32,
          34, 35.
    - title: 
      content: 'Then set up the courtyard around the outside of the tent, and hang
        the curtain for the courtyard entrance.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CTake the anointing oil and anoint the Tabernacle and all its
        furnishings to consecrate them and make them holy. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Anoint the altar of burnt offering and its utensils to consecrate
        them. Then the altar will become absolutely holy. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Next anoint the washbasin and its stand to consecrate them.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CPresent Aaron and his sons at the entrance of the Tabernacle,
        and wash them with water. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Dress Aaron with the sacred garments and anoint him, consecrating
        him to serve me as a priest. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then present his sons and dress them in their tunics. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Anoint them as you did their father, so they may also serve me as
        priests. With their anointing, Aaron\u2019s descendants are set apart for
        the priesthood forever, from generation to generation.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Moses proceeded to do everything just as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        had commanded him. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So the Tabernacle was set up on the first day of the first month
        of the second year. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Moses erected the Tabernacle by setting down its bases, inserting
        the frames, attaching the crossbars, and setting up the posts. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then he spread the coverings over the Tabernacle framework and put
        on the protective layers, just as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had commanded
        him.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He took the stone tablets inscribed with the terms of the covenant
        and placed them[[COMMENT(0)]] inside the Ark. Then he attached the carrying
        poles to the Ark, and he set the Ark\u2019s cover\u2014the place of atonement\u2014on
        top of it. "
      comments:
      - number: '40:20 '
        content: Hebrew <b>He placed the Testimony; </b>see note on 25:16.
    - title: 
      content: 'Then he brought the Ark of the Covenant into the Tabernacle and hung
        the inner curtain to shield it from view, just as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        had commanded him.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Next Moses placed the table in the Tabernacle, along the north side
        of the Holy Place, just outside the inner curtain. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And he arranged the Bread of the Presence on the table before the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, just as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had
        commanded him.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He set the lampstand in the Tabernacle across from the table on the
        south side of the Holy Place. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then he lit the lamps in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s presence,
        just as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had commanded him. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He also placed the gold incense altar in the Tabernacle, in the Holy
        Place in front of the inner curtain. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'On it he burned the fragrant incense, just as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        had commanded him.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He hung the curtain at the entrance of the Tabernacle, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'and he placed the altar of burnt offering near the Tabernacle entrance.
        On it he offered a burnt offering and a grain offering, just as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        had commanded him.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Next Moses placed the washbasin between the Tabernacle and the altar.
        He filled it with water so the priests could wash themselves. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Moses and Aaron and Aaron\u2019s sons used water from it to wash
        their hands and feet. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Whenever they approached the altar and entered the Tabernacle, they
        washed themselves, just as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had commanded
        Moses.  '
      comments: []
    - title: "The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s Glory Fills the Tabernacle"
      content: 'Then he hung the curtains forming the courtyard around the Tabernacle
        and the altar. And he set up the curtain at the entrance of the courtyard.
        So at last Moses finished the work.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then the cloud covered the Tabernacle, and the glory of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        filled the Tabernacle. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Moses could no longer enter the Tabernacle because the cloud had
        settled down over it, and the glory of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> filled
        the Tabernacle.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Now whenever the cloud lifted from the Tabernacle, the people of
        Israel would set out on their journey, following it. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But if the cloud did not rise, they remained where they were until
        it lifted. '
      comments: []
